WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.260
[Amit Varma]: I love cities. Cities represent everything that is good about our species. Humans are

00:00:11.260 --> 00:00:16.180
[Amit Varma]: social animals. We learn and grow and prosper by interacting with each other, by trading

00:00:16.180 --> 00:00:21.340
[Amit Varma]: to mutual benefit. Cities are an engine of human prosperity. You know, people often invoke

00:00:21.340 --> 00:00:26.020
[Amit Varma]: the joys of rural living, of village life. But the history of humanity is a history of

00:00:26.020 --> 00:00:32.940
[Amit Varma]: migration out of rural areas into urban spaces. We want to be part of large economic networks,

00:00:32.940 --> 00:00:36.940
[Amit Varma]: which bring us opportunity. We want to be part of a bustling metropolis where there

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:41.940
[Amit Varma]: is a greater chance of our needs being fulfilled, where we can live the good life. And if you

00:00:41.940 --> 00:00:46.840
[Amit Varma]: disagree with this, ask yourself where you're located right now. Chances are you've already

00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:52.180
[Amit Varma]: voted with your feet. However, there is a big caveat to all of this. Cities are great

00:00:52.180 --> 00:00:57.060
[Amit Varma]: most of the time, but not when there's a pandemic going on. It's our cities that are hardest

00:00:57.060 --> 00:01:03.140
[Amit Varma]: hit by COVID-19 for obvious reasons. So many people so close together. How much social

00:01:03.140 --> 00:01:07.900
[Amit Varma]: distancing can we manage? And while I have no doubt that cities will continue to thrive

00:01:07.900 --> 00:01:13.740
[Amit Varma]: after this pandemic is behind us, the question remains, how much will COVID-19 change our

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:24.700
[Unknown]: cities? How much will COVID-19 change us and the way we live our lives?

00:01:24.700 --> 00:01:31.940
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral

00:01:31.940 --> 00:01:33.780
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Varma.

00:01:33.780 --> 00:01:38.460
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is Vaidahi Tandil, a scholar who works

00:01:38.460 --> 00:01:43.780
[Amit Varma]: at the IDFC Institute in Mumbai, and has been studying cities and writing about urbanization

00:01:43.780 --> 00:01:48.300
[Amit Varma]: for many years now. I've been thinking of inviting Vaidahi on the show for a long time,

00:01:48.300 --> 00:01:53.060
[Amit Varma]: and I finally got around to doing it now. The ostensible peg for our conversation was

00:01:53.060 --> 00:01:59.060
[Amit Varma]: how COVID would change our cities and what our cities need to do to combat COVID-19.

00:01:59.060 --> 00:02:02.900
[Amit Varma]: But we also took a step back and spoke about urbanization and the history of cities, as

00:02:02.900 --> 00:02:07.260
[Amit Varma]: also the field of economics itself. Before we get to our conversation, though, let's

00:02:07.260 --> 00:02:10.580
[Amit Varma]: take a quick emotional break.

00:02:10.580 --> 00:02:14.140
[Amit Varma]: If you enjoy listening to The Scene and the Unseen, you can play a part in keeping the

00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:19.180
[Amit Varma]: show alive. The Scene and the Unseen has been a labor of love for me. I've enjoyed putting

00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:24.660
[Amit Varma]: together many stimulating conversations, expanding my brain and my universe, and hopefully yours

00:02:24.660 --> 00:02:29.500
[Amit Varma]: as well. But while the work has been its own reward, I don't actually make much money off

