[Amit Varma]: woken up to the insane engagement level of podcasts, and I do many, many hours of deep

00:02:38.660 --> 00:02:44.620
[Amit Varma]: research for each episode, besides all the logistics of producing the show myself. Scheduling

00:02:44.620 --> 00:02:49.580
[Amit Varma]: guests, booking studios, paying technicians, the travel, and so on. So, well, I'm trying

00:02:49.580 --> 00:02:54.500
[Amit Varma]: a new way of keeping this thing going, and that involves you. My proposition for you

00:02:54.500 --> 00:02:59.300
[Amit Varma]: is this. For every episode of The Scene and the Unseen that you enjoy, buy me a cup of

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:04.420
[Amit Varma]: coffee, or even a lavish lunch, whatever you feel it's worth. You can do this by heading

00:03:04.420 --> 00:03:10.060
[Amit Varma]: over to sceneunseen.in slash support, and contributing an amount of your choice. This

00:03:10.060 --> 00:03:16.380
[Amit Varma]: is not a subscription. The Scene and the Unseen will continue to be free on all podcast apps

00:03:16.380 --> 00:03:23.980
[Amit Varma]: and at sceneunseen.in. This is just a gesture of appreciation. Help keep this thing going.

00:03:23.980 --> 00:03:36.180
[Amit Varma]: Thank you so much for having me, Amit. Yeah, it's been a while coming because our mutual

00:03:36.180 --> 00:03:40.300
[Amit Varma]: friend Shruti Rajagopalan keeps telling me that, you know, why don't you get Vaidehi

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:43.900
[Amit Varma]: on your show? What is wrong with you? You are both in Mumbai, which is of course true

00:03:43.900 --> 00:03:50.300
[Amit Varma]: though now, both of us being in Mumbai is sort of a moot point in these days. So, now

00:03:50.300 --> 00:03:54.620
[Amit Varma]: that you know, you're finally on the show, and we've bumped into each other at events,

00:03:54.620 --> 00:03:59.500
[Amit Varma]: but never actually had a conversation. So I'm looking kind of looking forward to knowing

00:03:59.500 --> 00:04:03.780
[Amit Varma]: more about where you come from, and so on. So tell me a bit about, you know, your journey

00:04:03.780 --> 00:04:08.460
[Amit Varma]: so far, not just your journey in terms of academics and career and all of that, but

00:04:08.460 --> 00:04:14.260
[Amit Varma]: also in terms of, you know, your intellectual journey, what are your influences? What are

00:04:14.260 --> 00:04:21.460
[Guest]: the things that have shaped you? Right, so I started off wanting to be a journalist actually

00:04:21.460 --> 00:04:28.820
[Guest]: in school. And so I always knew I wanted to get a BA. So I scored decent enough for me

00:04:28.820 --> 00:04:34.340
[Guest]: to get into Xavier. So that was like a big thing. And I wanted to major in literature

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:40.460
[Guest]: back then. But you have to choose other subjects along with your, you know, main major. So

00:04:40.460 --> 00:04:46.140
[Guest]: I've taken economics. And we didn't have economics at school before that was only in the 11th

00:04:46.140 --> 00:04:52.460
[Guest]: and 12th. That was the first time I got exposed to economics, you know, as a discipline, and

00:04:52.460 --> 00:04:59.300
[Guest]: it kind of blew my mind. And I sort of eventually veered away from literature, and then ended

00:04:59.300 --> 00:05:05.980
[Guest]: up dumping it for economics and ended up majoring in economics. Went on to do my master's again,

00:05:05.980 --> 00:05:13.420
[Guest]: by then journalism was no longer a dream as such, I was thinking more about getting into

00:05:13.420 --> 00:05:20.020
[Guest]: academia. And my master's really helped because I mean, it was at that time, you know, the

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:25.060
[Guest]: Department of Economics, it started its first semester course, and we were like the second

00:05:25.060 --> 00:05:30.180
[Guest]: batch to enter this new course with a lot more rigor and you know, a proper semester

00:05:30.180 --> 00:05:36.180
[Guest]: based system and we had excellent professors. Many of them sadly have retired now. But at

00:05:36.180 --> 00:05:42.660
[Guest]: that time, it was a great environment to study. You know, we really got down into the weeds

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:48.540
[Guest]: and you know, both in mathematical, you know, formality of the treatment of the subject,

00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:55.020
[Guest]: as well as going beyond neoclassical economics to discover other things like, you know, institutional

00:05:55.020 --> 00:06:02.100
[Guest]: economics, public choice theory, and the kind of electives I picked back then were extremely

00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:08.300
[Guest]: important and useful in how I've ended up looking at policies and looking and where

00:06:08.300 --> 00:06:15.300
[Guest]: my research has taken me. So that was sort of like a journey in terms of the academic

00:06:15.300 --> 00:06:20.940
[Guest]: journey. And I eventually ended up doing my PhD under one of my professors back then,

00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:28.340
[Guest]: who was at the department, and it ended up being in urban economics, but I approached

00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:34.220
[Guest]: it from a political economy lens, looking at things like transactions, cost economics

00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:41.980
[Guest]: and so on. And yeah, and then since then, I mean, I think I've been at IDFC Institute,

00:06:41.980 --> 00:06:48.860
[Guest]: which is the research policy think tank in Mumbai. And you've had guests on the show,

00:06:48.860 --> 00:06:56.620
[Guest]: you know, been my colleagues. So I've been here since 2014. I took one year off to get

00:06:56.620 --> 00:07:03.500
[Guest]: a postdoc at Columbia. But I've been here since and been basically working on public

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:09.140
[Guest]: policy research in urban areas and also in business regulatory environment.

00:07:09.140 --> 00:07:14.940
[Amit Varma]: I find a couple of strands intriguing here. One is that, you know, you said, you know,

00:07:14.940 --> 00:07:20.100
[Amit Varma]: beginning to study economics blew your mind. And I was curious about why this is so because,

00:07:20.100 --> 00:07:23.540
[Amit Varma]: you know, I remember, you know, back from my time, and I didn't study economics, actually

00:07:23.540 --> 00:07:27.460
[Amit Varma]: studied literature. And but I remember from that time that the economics that was taught

00:07:27.460 --> 00:07:33.060
[Amit Varma]: in Indian colleges was just boring and dull. And basically, it was meant to drive you away

00:07:33.060 --> 00:07:37.620
[Amit Varma]: from the subject. And it wasn't interesting at all. So, you know, was this particular

00:07:37.620 --> 00:07:42.420
[Amit Varma]: course different in that sense? And the other question regarding this I have is that one

00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:48.300
[Amit Varma]: lemon that I have heard even from economists is that a lot of modern economics training

00:07:48.300 --> 00:07:54.020
[Amit Varma]: is too focused on data and the math and the econometrics and all of that. And you are

00:07:54.020 --> 00:07:59.620
[Amit Varma]: no longer sort of looking at broad concepts to make sense of the world. Like, you know,

00:07:59.620 --> 00:08:04.300
[Amit Varma]: one of the ways in which I think literature and economics actually related is that they

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:09.820
[Amit Varma]: both give you insight into human behavior. And that's always why I've been like economics

00:08:09.820 --> 00:08:14.380
[Amit Varma]: is, you know, at different times, I've never been formally trained, blown my mind as well.

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:18.620
[Amit Varma]: So I'd be interested in knowing, you know, what are the ways in which it blew your mind?

00:08:18.620 --> 00:08:23.300
[Amit Varma]: Did you sort of contextualize learnings of economics to your through the life around

00:08:23.300 --> 00:08:27.340
[Amit Varma]: you and realize that, hey, these are not arcane things, these really matter?

00:08:27.340 --> 00:08:33.220
[Guest]: I very vividly remember my first class in economics, where they teach you the principle

00:08:33.220 --> 00:08:38.860
[Guest]: of diminishing marginal utility. And it's a very simple sort of class, very non technical.

00:08:38.860 --> 00:08:43.340
[Guest]: I mean, they'll draw a graph, which was a downward curve, and there'll be like, mangoes

00:08:43.340 --> 00:08:49.780
[Guest]: on the one side, and like, your y axis will be a utility. And basically saying, the more

00:08:49.780 --> 00:08:56.020
[Guest]: mangoes you have, the additional one appeals less and less to you. And I was just like,

00:08:56.020 --> 00:09:02.500
[Guest]: wait, there's a term for this, you know, and, and that was just like, what's going on. So

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:09.740
[Guest]: I think from then on, it was, it's not like the course we had was very, you know, amazing

00:09:09.740 --> 00:09:16.580
[Guest]: or very up to date in terms of, it's a Mumbai University undergraduate economics course.

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:23.300
[Guest]: So very, very basic stuff, catered to like a very, you know, non mathematical sort of

00:09:23.300 --> 00:09:29.900
[Guest]: a batch of students. But still, it was things like this that I kept on discovering, which

00:09:29.900 --> 00:09:36.460
[Guest]: I was like, Oh, I mean, this sort of makes sense. It just ended up answering questions

00:09:36.460 --> 00:09:43.420
[Guest]: that I didn't know I had. And it allowed me to understand and name concepts like opportunity

00:09:43.420 --> 00:09:49.340
[Guest]: costs, for instance. That was another thing. I was like, Oh, wait, yeah, this, this makes

00:09:49.340 --> 00:09:56.100
[Guest]: sense. And there's a word for it. So I can now actually use it and make sense of the

00:09:56.100 --> 00:10:03.780
[Guest]: more sense of the world around me. So these, these ideas were the ones that were what attracted

00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:09.420
[Guest]: me to it. And what drew I mean, it's so the love for literature continued, I dropped it

00:10:09.420 --> 00:10:15.660
[Guest]: only in my third year, I was doing lit in in first year and second year, but it allowed

00:10:15.660 --> 00:10:24.100
[Guest]: me structure, whereas literature was there for me to get into the motivations of people,

00:10:24.100 --> 00:10:29.660
[Guest]: the inner motivations for people, of people, what economics was allowing me to do was looking

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:36.220
[Guest]: at systems. And like, you know, looking from a systems approach, I could not find a better

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:42.020
[Guest]: way of, of trying to explain the world around me. So yeah, so I think that's, that's how

00:10:42.020 --> 00:10:47.820
[Guest]: I feel the the tools sort of helped me look at the world in very different ways. But I

00:10:47.820 --> 00:10:55.660
[Guest]: mean, equally important ways about your question about, you know, the formal, the math obsession

00:10:55.660 --> 00:11:03.780
[Guest]: in economics, it exists, and it's been a product of a number of factors. So I mean, we don't

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:09.180
[Guest]: I don't want to get into that, because that's probably another episode. And I don't think

00:11:09.180 --> 00:11:13.740
[Guest]: I'm the best person to talk about it, because I only learned as much as was enough for me

00:11:13.740 --> 00:11:21.540
[Guest]: to, you know, get by. But I think there was a period of time when there was a lot of empiricism.

00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:27.860
[Guest]: So the econometrics and the empiricism and the like the clever ways in which you define

00:11:27.860 --> 00:11:33.740
[Guest]: your identification strategies, which is basically the way in which you establish a causal relationship

00:11:33.740 --> 00:11:42.100
[Guest]: between x phenomenon and a y phenomenon, that led to a lot of emphasis on showing off these

00:11:42.100 --> 00:11:49.940
[Guest]: various types of identification strategies. So your role, you know, emphasis was on looking

00:11:49.940 --> 00:11:58.820
[Guest]: for not the questions, but what is the interesting data that with which I can do some fancy stuff

00:11:58.820 --> 00:12:05.780
[Guest]: and have a nice relationship. But I think over time, there has been shift back to looking

00:12:05.780 --> 00:12:13.980
[Guest]: at some of the fundamental things. And I think we've gone to sort of balancing the two things.

00:12:13.980 --> 00:12:20.300
[Guest]: So I feel for instance, I really like the work that so Karthik, who was on your show,

00:12:20.300 --> 00:12:26.060
[Guest]: so his work, then the stuff that Raj Chetty do on social mobility, and these questions

00:12:26.060 --> 00:12:34.060
[Guest]: are extremely fundamental for us as a society. So they're not looking at trivial questions.

00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:38.340
[Guest]: And they're in it for like, they're really, really committed to this. It's not like they're

00:12:38.340 --> 00:12:43.300
[Guest]: moving from one interesting problem to the next, because, you know, they just want to

00:12:43.300 --> 00:12:48.860
[Guest]: show off their tricks. But it's a deep commitment. And, and they bring a lot of a mathematical

00:12:48.860 --> 00:12:54.220
[Guest]: result to try and understand it. So I'm not complaining, to be honest, in terms of where

00:12:54.220 --> 00:13:00.380
[Guest]: it's moved now, perhaps 20 years, or even 10 years earlier, it may have been the case

00:13:00.380 --> 00:13:05.620
[Guest]: that there was, or perhaps I'm just reading the ones, the people I like. So I think that

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:11.820
[Guest]: this is how things have moved on, whereas, whereas the reality is completely different.

00:13:11.820 --> 00:13:17.180
[Amit Varma]: And reading the ones you like also has a word for it, which is selection bias. Sort of a

00:13:17.180 --> 00:13:21.780
[Amit Varma]: tangential question here, when you when you spoke about how, you know, Karthik and Raj

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:27.780
[Amit Varma]: Chetty are not sort of just showing off, you know, their tricks. And, you know, the thought

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:32.380
[Amit Varma]: that struck me earlier, when you were talking about how, you know, people would get carried

00:13:32.380 --> 00:13:37.300
[Amit Varma]: away with their econometric models, and just try to show everything is, you know, I'm reminded,

00:13:37.300 --> 00:13:41.340
[Amit Varma]: and this is a bit of a tangent, but I'm reminded of this essay that the philosopher Agnes Callard

00:13:41.340 --> 00:13:45.780
[Amit Varma]: wrote recently, where which are linked from the show notes, of course, and where she sort

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:50.500
[Amit Varma]: of was speaking about why academic writing is so dense. And her point there was that

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:55.660
[Amit Varma]: once you get on a tenure track, you're expected to publish in certain journals and blah, blah,

00:13:55.660 --> 00:14:00.660
[Amit Varma]: blah. And those journals have their own conventions and so on. And therefore, you have to follow

00:14:00.660 --> 00:14:05.780
[Amit Varma]: those conventions. And what you are therefore writing for is to get accepted into those

00:14:05.780 --> 00:14:11.100
[Amit Varma]: journals and not to really make your writing have an impact on the wider world at large.

00:14:11.100 --> 00:14:16.420
[Amit Varma]: And would there be a similar thing with, you know, the use of math and economics, where

00:14:16.420 --> 00:14:22.500
[Amit Varma]: at one point in time, you know, using complicated econometrics became almost a way of signaling

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:27.620
[Amit Varma]: to your peers, or the sort of people around you of how sophisticated your work is, and

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:33.340
[Amit Varma]: how rigorous you are, and blah, blah, blah, and not really having that sort of an impact

00:14:33.340 --> 00:14:39.420
[Amit Varma]: on a wider readership. And also, you know, and you haven't really been an academic per

00:14:39.420 --> 00:14:46.060
[Amit Varma]: se, thankfully, but is there, therefore, some kind of dichotomy within, you know, academics

00:14:46.060 --> 00:14:50.660
[Amit Varma]: or within the field of economics, for example, where, you know, there is a trade off between

00:14:50.660 --> 00:14:54.820
[Amit Varma]: how much you can change the world by actually having an impact on the real world and studying

00:14:54.820 --> 00:15:00.700
[Amit Varma]: things that matter in the real world as, you know, Karthik and Raj do, and you do, in fact,

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:06.500
[Amit Varma]: or so is there a, you know, trade off between that and just doing impressive work, which

00:15:06.500 --> 00:15:10.100
[Amit Varma]: will sort of get you ahead or get you noticed?

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:18.020
[Guest]: So I think that most of the people, again, I have, I've only looked at this in your track

00:15:18.020 --> 00:15:24.660
[Guest]: system, miles away sitting here in India. So I'm going to add that as a huge caveat

00:15:24.660 --> 00:15:32.260
[Guest]: in what I'm going to say. My sense is that in the field of economics, at least, the work

00:15:32.260 --> 00:15:40.740
[Guest]: that the established tenured professors do is very different from the ones who are just

00:15:40.740 --> 00:15:46.700
[Guest]: out of the job market. So for the ones who are just out of the job market, the incentives

00:15:46.700 --> 00:15:52.940
[Guest]: are very different, right? You need to produce in certain journals for about five years.

00:15:52.940 --> 00:16:00.620
[Guest]: But as I guess, if you study the kinds of papers, let's say, an above average econ grad

00:16:00.620 --> 00:16:06.700
[Guest]: writes at the beginning of their career, and then how and as they sort of progress, you

00:16:06.700 --> 00:16:13.020
[Guest]: know, once they get tenure and the work that they do after, I think that it will change.

00:16:13.020 --> 00:16:18.180
[Guest]: My sense is that you will start off with, you know, just trying to get published and

00:16:18.180 --> 00:16:22.460
[Guest]: at least have those one two papers, because it takes a long time, like a life cycle of

00:16:22.460 --> 00:16:27.900
[Guest]: papers, five years, you know, if you want to get into a top journal. So it takes a long

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:33.140
[Guest]: time. So you will, you know, try and see what the work you're doing is sort of going to

00:16:33.140 --> 00:16:41.180
[Guest]: get you published. And so it's more geared towards that. Once those constraints are relaxed,

00:16:41.180 --> 00:16:47.660
[Guest]: that's when the sort of real, I guess, not real, I mean, I don't mean the effort, these

00:16:47.660 --> 00:16:55.940
[Guest]: are like very, very soul crushing, you know, type of work that that people do and the kind

00:16:55.940 --> 00:17:01.340
[Guest]: of journeys that they undertake. But once you're established, I think that that's when

00:17:01.340 --> 00:17:07.620
[Guest]: you start doing the long term stuff, start looking at taking on larger projects, and

00:17:07.620 --> 00:17:14.300
[Guest]: sort of expanding and trying to impact policy. And so the, you know, the classics of the

00:17:14.300 --> 00:17:20.540
[Guest]: world, the Jonathan Grubers of the world, and the, they all sort of come into their

00:17:20.540 --> 00:17:28.500
[Guest]: own at the later part of post tenure. So that's the, that's what my take is. So it's about

00:17:28.500 --> 00:17:34.420
[Guest]: like, just early stage career versus later stage career, the incentives that exist there

00:17:34.420 --> 00:17:38.460
[Guest]: and that lead into the kind of work that happens.

00:17:38.460 --> 00:17:41.980
[Amit Varma]: I like the phrase, the Karthiks of the world, I hope Karthik is listening, it becomes a

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:46.740
[Amit Varma]: popular phrase. And it also, you know, I was kind of struck by what you just said about

00:17:46.740 --> 00:17:51.620
[Amit Varma]: the life cycle of a paper being five years, because that whole system of academic publishing,

00:17:51.620 --> 00:17:56.020
[Amit Varma]: the long time lags, the whole peer review system seems so nonsensical and bizarre to

00:17:56.020 --> 00:17:59.380
[Amit Varma]: me, I understand that there are trade offs involved. But, you know, just sitting on the

00:17:59.380 --> 00:18:03.980
[Amit Varma]: outside, it seems like it's completely, you know, warped on one side, and the kind of

00:18:03.980 --> 00:18:07.260
[Amit Varma]: work you do, of course, is very different. I was struck by, you know, you were saying

00:18:07.260 --> 00:18:13.300
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, when you did your master's, and you studied further, your sort of specialization

00:18:13.300 --> 00:18:18.900
[Amit Varma]: area was urbanism, with a focus on the political economy, you know, both of these going together,

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:24.060
[Amit Varma]: which kind of made me sit up, because I thought it's almost as if, you know, IDFC Institute

00:18:24.060 --> 00:18:28.260
[Amit Varma]: went back in time, and they gave the requirements to the university, and then they produced

00:18:28.260 --> 00:18:34.340
[Amit Varma]: you because that's sort of exactly both what you do now. And I think what in these times

00:18:34.340 --> 00:18:39.580
[Amit Varma]: is necessary now, I mean, we need a scholarship and work in these areas. So tell me a bit

00:18:39.580 --> 00:18:44.620
[Amit Varma]: about what drew you to that specific subject at that time.

00:18:44.620 --> 00:18:51.500
[Guest]: There was a bunch of things. So I've lived in a city all my life. And initially, as a

00:18:51.500 --> 00:18:57.220
[Guest]: kid, I remember like completely hating it. Because I used to long to, you know, get out

00:18:57.220 --> 00:19:01.540
[Guest]: of the city and go on trips with my parents and family holidays and things like that.

00:19:01.540 --> 00:19:07.540
[Guest]: And we used to hate railway stations and all the crowds around. If you come to Mumbai,

00:19:07.540 --> 00:19:15.020
[Guest]: you know, there's enough reason for you to hate Mumbai. But as I think, grew, I guess,

00:19:15.020 --> 00:19:20.380
[Guest]: I mean, in my college days, I was when I realized that, okay, there's some reason why people

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:27.340
[Guest]: are coming here. And it does seem to be making, you know, life easier for people. And you

00:19:27.340 --> 00:19:32.900
[Guest]: could see this from, I mean, I could see this, as I grew up, I realized my parents also had

00:19:32.900 --> 00:19:38.340
[Guest]: the same journey, rather, my grandfather did, he moved to a city, if he had stayed back

00:19:38.340 --> 00:19:43.420
[Guest]: in the village, he would not have got the opportunity that he did, when he moved. Of

00:19:43.420 --> 00:19:47.500
[Guest]: course, it helped that there was social networks in the city that, you know, allowed him to

00:19:47.500 --> 00:19:52.780
[Guest]: get a foothold and so on. And it has two generations on the line, you know, it's made a difference

00:19:52.780 --> 00:20:00.540
[Guest]: to how we live. So those kinds of things sort of struck me. And, again, I think the art

00:20:00.540 --> 00:20:06.820
[Guest]: department was among the handful of departments in the country that offers a paper on urban

00:20:06.820 --> 00:20:13.220
[Guest]: economics. So I said, Okay, let's take it. And I along with this, so I took an elective

00:20:13.220 --> 00:20:20.300
[Guest]: on public choice theory, and I took another elective on just trade, basically, we had

00:20:20.300 --> 00:20:28.020
[Guest]: an international trade. And I feel like all of these sort of have, you know, they do combine.

00:20:28.020 --> 00:20:32.780
[Guest]: And so it's, when I actually ended up sitting on for my first urban eco lecture, it was

00:20:32.780 --> 00:20:39.020
[Guest]: very similar to what happened when I sat in my first eco lecture, you know, where my professor

00:20:39.020 --> 00:20:44.380
[Guest]: who later went on to be my PhD supervisor was, was trying to explain to us what what's

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:50.660
[Guest]: the secret sauce? Why? Why do cities prosper? And what makes some cities grow and prosper?

00:20:50.660 --> 00:20:57.060
[Guest]: And why do some cities fail? And, and so it just, again, it gave me a lot more insight

00:20:57.060 --> 00:21:04.220
[Guest]: and understanding. And, you know, after my master, I was talking with the I knew I wanted

00:21:04.220 --> 00:21:10.020
[Guest]: to do a PhD anyway. So I was going between like, moving, you know, taking a gap year,

00:21:10.020 --> 00:21:15.300
[Guest]: getting some research work, and then moving to the US or staying here. And I, I knew that

00:21:15.300 --> 00:21:21.740
[Guest]: I'd only stay if my then urban eco professor said he'd take me on as a student, and he

00:21:21.740 --> 00:21:26.620
[Guest]: was happy to so I said, Okay, let's I have no reason to go then it's fine. I mean, life

00:21:26.620 --> 00:21:33.660
[Guest]: is nice. You know, you have you can be at home, you can do your thesis and, and the

00:21:33.660 --> 00:21:40.260
[Guest]: university is lovely. If you visited it at any point in Kalina, it's a nice green place,

00:21:40.260 --> 00:21:43.780
[Guest]: you have nice chai. So I was like, fine, this looks good.

00:21:43.780 --> 00:21:48.380
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, it's very interesting. I used to pass the university almost every day, because

00:21:48.380 --> 00:21:52.420
[Amit Varma]: I used to be a professional poker player for five years. And one of the games I regularly

00:21:52.420 --> 00:21:57.140
[Amit Varma]: played illegal underground games, of course, was in New Mumbai. So I would go there via

00:21:57.140 --> 00:22:02.420
[Amit Varma]: the SCLR. And therefore, and I hated the thought of the university, because that was the most

00:22:02.420 --> 00:22:08.180
[Amit Varma]: crowded road, that particular stretch, but that's a bizarre and completely unrequired

00:22:08.180 --> 00:22:14.100
[Amit Varma]: tangent, in contrast with most of the engines I take. So and also, you mentioned sort of

00:22:14.100 --> 00:22:20.060
[Amit Varma]: the political economy aspect of it. And then you sort of joined IDFC Institute, which calls

00:22:20.060 --> 00:22:26.020
[Amit Varma]: itself a think and do tank. So where, you know, the whole idea is that we don't just

00:22:26.020 --> 00:22:29.940
[Amit Varma]: think about things and diagnose that, oh, this is a problem. And this is what we should

00:22:29.940 --> 00:22:35.740
[Amit Varma]: do. But you actually try to work with the state and kind of getting things done. So

00:22:35.740 --> 00:22:40.060
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit about that difference between a think tank and a think and do tank.

00:22:40.060 --> 00:22:44.500
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, how does that affect the work that you do? Does all your work then have

00:22:44.500 --> 00:22:50.260
[Amit Varma]: this extra layer of, you know, how practical is it to make things happen in this area?

00:22:50.260 --> 00:22:55.540
[Amit Varma]: So are you not just whenever you're studying x, are you not just studying x, but also x

00:22:55.540 --> 00:23:00.300
[Guest]: plus the government's role in whatever it can do?

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:07.900
[Guest]: That's an interesting question, because I have not looked at the work that I do from,

00:23:07.900 --> 00:23:16.340
[Guest]: you know, how feasible it will be to get it implemented. It's always been about we've

00:23:16.340 --> 00:23:22.380
[Guest]: been lucky that as you mentioned, right, it's a nice match where the questions that excited

00:23:22.380 --> 00:23:28.300
[Guest]: me or the questions that the Institute was waiting to and wanting to investigate. So

00:23:28.300 --> 00:23:35.820
[Guest]: the way we started out doing work was, we were a very small organization. And Ruben,

00:23:35.820 --> 00:23:41.700
[Guest]: my boss, he sort of let us, gave us a free run. He said, you know, what interests you,

00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:47.420
[Guest]: what excites you? Why don't you take up a research idea that you think, you know, you

00:23:47.420 --> 00:23:54.220
[Guest]: will be able to deliver on? So first work that I did along with my colleague Komal Hiranandani

00:23:54.220 --> 00:24:01.180
[Guest]: and Mudit Kapoor, who was then a visiting fellow, he's an associate professor at ISI

00:24:01.180 --> 00:24:10.540
[Guest]: Delhi. So three of us were working, we started working on this idea of trying to measure

00:24:10.540 --> 00:24:17.860
[Guest]: urbanization in the country, using a different metric than what the government uses, to try

00:24:17.860 --> 00:24:22.620
[Guest]: and see whether India is different, and whether India looks different, whether it's more urban

00:24:22.620 --> 00:24:29.100
[Guest]: than the official definition seem to suggest. And official definitions, I mean, suggest

00:24:29.100 --> 00:24:35.580
[Guest]: that we are 31% urban. And that's the census definition. If you, if you look at the just,

00:24:35.580 --> 00:24:41.260
[Guest]: if you just count the number of municipal areas in the country, then that would account

00:24:41.260 --> 00:24:47.900
[Guest]: for 26% of the country's population. So it's even lower. And it's surprising given India's

00:24:47.900 --> 00:24:53.700
[Guest]: per capita incomes, you know, about, we're fairly rich, but our urbanization rates are

00:24:53.700 --> 00:24:59.260
[Guest]: not reflecting that. So is that a quirk of the definition that we're using? That's the

00:24:59.260 --> 00:25:05.500
[Guest]: path we took. It led to some interesting insights, some interesting results, we can discuss that

00:25:05.500 --> 00:25:14.340
[Guest]: later at a later stage. But what we realized is, is where sort of the do piece comes is

00:25:14.340 --> 00:25:20.500
[Guest]: the fact that we tend to speak, we don't just keep think about research as a product that

00:25:20.500 --> 00:25:27.460
[Guest]: will be printed in a journal or as a report and be kept on the shelves. But actively speaking

00:25:27.460 --> 00:25:36.660
[Guest]: to government policy experts about it. And of course, sort of, it helps to have built

00:25:36.660 --> 00:25:42.900
[Guest]: so and this, this is the strength that say, Ruben brought, where he is, you know, well

00:25:42.900 --> 00:25:48.460
[Guest]: networked, and he knows that, you know, he'd be able to interest not just Indian experts,

00:25:48.460 --> 00:25:54.020
[Guest]: but even international experts in the kind of research findings that that we were producing.

00:25:54.020 --> 00:26:00.540
[Guest]: So we could do a lot of presentations, we've presented at various forums, you know, to

00:26:00.540 --> 00:26:07.100
[Guest]: the government to other urban experts, to even bureaucrats in various. So it's a lot

00:26:07.100 --> 00:26:12.220
[Guest]: about actually going and talking about it and trying to sort of, it's the marketing

00:26:12.220 --> 00:26:17.580
[Guest]: piece. And it's equally important, because we believed in the rigor of our research,

00:26:17.580 --> 00:26:23.140
[Guest]: and we believed in the findings. And we knew we had enough analytical rigor to stand on

00:26:23.140 --> 00:26:28.420
[Guest]: to be able to go and present. So that's the sort of approach that the Institute takes.

00:26:28.420 --> 00:26:34.260
[Guest]: It's about a like creating the research and using enough rigor. I mean, we don't want

00:26:34.260 --> 00:26:38.740
[Guest]: to necessarily publish, you know, in the top five journals. So it's certainly not going

00:26:38.740 --> 00:26:43.500
[Guest]: to be that level of rigor where you're looking at the number of asterisks on your coefficient

00:26:43.500 --> 00:26:51.180
[Guest]: and so on. But it's enough that it will pass like, you know, any scrutiny, any sensible

00:26:51.180 --> 00:26:57.700
[Guest]: sort of person can see the logic. And, you know, that was the way in which we thought

00:26:57.700 --> 00:27:03.420
[Guest]: about the research that we do. And of course, like, ensuring that you write op-eds, ensuring

00:27:03.420 --> 00:27:10.380
[Guest]: that you speak to people, ends up sort of, you know, having some impact, I will again

00:27:10.380 --> 00:27:16.620
[Guest]: not say, in a policy space, again, this is stuff that some of that Ruben and others also

00:27:16.620 --> 00:27:20.940
[Guest]: say that in the policy space, you can really make no positive claims in the work that you

00:27:20.940 --> 00:27:26.700
[Guest]: do and the, and the policies that get framed. In fact, you know, you should, one can't make

00:27:26.700 --> 00:27:33.820
[Guest]: any, any causal claims, because that's disingenuous in a certain sense. But, but talking to people

00:27:33.820 --> 00:27:41.700
[Guest]: is something that is what every sort of serious research slash policy expert has to do. You

00:27:41.700 --> 00:27:45.380
[Guest]: have to keep talking, you have to keep writing for the lay public.

00:27:45.380 --> 00:27:50.020
[Amit Varma]: Ruben's been a good friend for like, almost 15 years. And the way I have often described

00:27:50.020 --> 00:27:53.420
[Amit Varma]: him as a way that you just described him that one, of course, he's one of the most brilliant

00:27:53.420 --> 00:27:57.860
[Amit Varma]: people I know. But also, he is by far the best networker I know. And not networker in

00:27:57.860 --> 00:28:02.500
[Amit Varma]: a sense of for the schmoozy kind of networker, but the networker in terms of actually getting

00:28:02.500 --> 00:28:06.980
[Amit Varma]: things done. I mean, to use Gladwell's terms, he's not just a connector, but also a maven,

00:28:06.980 --> 00:28:12.940
[Amit Varma]: which is a sort of a unique combination. I had Ruben and Pitika on the show last year.

00:28:12.940 --> 00:28:16.620
[Amit Varma]: And in an episode I linked from the show notes where we spoke about precisely that study

00:28:16.620 --> 00:28:22.780
[Amit Varma]: how India is more urban than most people think up to 45% urban. And you know, as you pointed

00:28:22.780 --> 00:28:28.940
[Amit Varma]: out in a piece you wrote this January with two co authors, where, you know, you pointed

00:28:28.940 --> 00:28:34.860
[Amit Varma]: out that if you take the metric of 5000 people as as an urban area, Kerala is actually 100%

00:28:34.860 --> 00:28:39.140
[Amit Varma]: urban, you know, so that whole statistic that came earlier in the year, the three of the

00:28:39.140 --> 00:28:45.060
[Amit Varma]: 10 fastest growing cities in the world are in Kerala. And that makes sense. And although

00:28:45.060 --> 00:28:49.580
[Amit Varma]: I covered this area with Ruben and Pitika, but nevertheless, give me a sense of why this

00:28:49.580 --> 00:28:57.140
[Amit Varma]: matters is this whole sense of what is defined as an urban area and what is not I mean, obviously

00:28:57.140 --> 00:29:03.060
[Amit Varma]: definitions matter, because whatever is defined as an urban area is ruled by an urban body

00:29:03.060 --> 00:29:07.740
[Amit Varma]: with its own rules. So your roads have to be this wide. And these are the services that

00:29:07.740 --> 00:29:12.220
[Amit Varma]: have to be provided. And a rural governing body doesn't have those same restrictions.

00:29:12.220 --> 00:29:17.020
[Amit Varma]: So you get a different quality of service. So tell me briefly, you know, why it matters

00:29:17.020 --> 00:29:22.860
[Amit Varma]: and what is sort of holding us back from recognizing that, you know, we are as urban as we actually

00:29:22.860 --> 00:29:34.220
[Guest]: are. So why it matters is something that, as you mentioned, every place, if you go to

00:29:34.220 --> 00:29:39.940
[Guest]: the fundamentals of it, what distinguishes a rural area from an urban area is that the

00:29:39.940 --> 00:29:45.140
[Guest]: urban urban areas tend to be denser, they tend to be larger in size, and their base

00:29:45.140 --> 00:29:52.580
[Guest]: of economic activity is not agriculture. Right. And so they're fundamentally different from

00:29:52.580 --> 00:29:59.380
[Guest]: a rural place. So they don't require irrigation facilities, they require, say, building bylaws,

00:29:59.380 --> 00:30:04.420
[Guest]: right, where, which allow you to have some mixed use zoning and so on, and allow you

00:30:04.420 --> 00:30:13.460
[Guest]: to build a non agricultural sort of construction and so on. So their needs are different there.

00:30:13.460 --> 00:30:18.700
[Guest]: And it's again, it's coming from the fact that urban areas have something that that

00:30:18.700 --> 00:30:25.820
[Guest]: rural areas don't, which is economies of scale and agglomeration economies, right. So what

00:30:25.820 --> 00:30:31.380
[Guest]: the large populations what the densities allow you to do is a bunch of things, they allow

00:30:31.380 --> 00:30:38.420
[Guest]: you to share ideas faster, because you, you tend to meet a lot more people, innovators,

00:30:38.420 --> 00:30:43.860
[Guest]: famously, you know, a lot of the innovations come from the from the most urban parts of

00:30:43.860 --> 00:30:48.620
[Guest]: the world and people will pay a premium to look at that you have, you know, very high

00:30:48.620 --> 00:30:54.140
[Guest]: talent, you will want to locate in a place where there are other talented people and

00:30:54.140 --> 00:31:01.900
[Guest]: smart people like you. So that's, that's one of the reasons why the urban sort of the densities

00:31:01.900 --> 00:31:08.660
[Guest]: and the sizes of the city is sort of self reinforcing. So once you have high productivity

00:31:08.660 --> 00:31:12.940
[Guest]: advantages from being in the city, it will attract more people, which will again lead

00:31:12.940 --> 00:31:20.420
[Guest]: to higher productivity. But there's a downside to this, which is, you know, I think, I forget

00:31:20.420 --> 00:31:28.060
[Guest]: who it was, but there's that three famous disagglomeration effects. One is congestion,

00:31:28.060 --> 00:31:34.940
[Guest]: one is crime, and contagion. So three Cs. And that's why you need a different type of

00:31:34.940 --> 00:31:39.380
[Guest]: because these externalities exist, you need different types of governance mechanisms for

00:31:39.380 --> 00:31:46.940
[Guest]: cities as compared to villages and rural areas. Now, what happens is when you apply a definition

00:31:46.940 --> 00:31:51.740
[Guest]: for urban versus rural area, the underlying assumption is that your definition is accurately

00:31:51.740 --> 00:31:57.180
[Guest]: identifying a settlement as urban. When you apply a definition that does not do that.

00:31:57.180 --> 00:32:02.380
[Guest]: So suppose you apply a definition that is extremely strict, like India's definition

00:32:02.380 --> 00:32:09.980
[Guest]: is, you may end up, you know, misclassifying urban areas of village. And then that means

00:32:09.980 --> 00:32:16.180
[Guest]: that even though there are these potential agglomeration effects that there are no governance

00:32:16.180 --> 00:32:24.380
[Guest]: systems that can mitigate the disagglomeration. Right? So that's the issue. If you misclassify,

00:32:24.380 --> 00:32:28.340
[Guest]: and that's why it's important to correctly classify. The other reason it's important

00:32:28.340 --> 00:32:34.420
[Guest]: to correctly classify is because, at least in India, you have several schemes that are

00:32:34.420 --> 00:32:40.140
[Guest]: targeted only to rural areas. And this has come out again, in the current debate, where

00:32:40.140 --> 00:32:45.060
[Guest]: now there's some debate on having an urban employment guarantee scheme, because what

00:32:45.060 --> 00:32:50.580
[Guest]: you think is traditionally because rural areas have worse off in terms of socioeconomic characteristics,

00:32:50.580 --> 00:32:54.980
[Guest]: you need to give them special benefits, you need to have special schemes, special programs

00:32:54.980 --> 00:33:01.380
[Guest]: to rural areas. But if you are misidentifying the rural areas, that means that some of the

00:33:01.380 --> 00:33:08.020
[Guest]: money is going to urban like rural areas, right? And that's a misclassification of resources.

00:33:08.020 --> 00:33:12.700
[Guest]: You can obviously debate the need for this rural urban classification based on current

00:33:12.700 --> 00:33:19.260
[Guest]: definitions. Because, to me, if you are going to implement a scheme that will help the vulnerable

00:33:19.260 --> 00:33:24.300
[Guest]: people, it should be targeted to the people irrespective of where they live. Like, I mean,

00:33:24.300 --> 00:33:28.980
[Guest]: this one first filter of where they live, and then identifying the households within

00:33:28.980 --> 00:33:35.580
[Guest]: those areas is, to me, you know, a very inefficient way of going about doing things. But it's

00:33:35.580 --> 00:33:40.180
[Guest]: convenient, it's easy, or I guess it's easy to implement, because we have traditional

00:33:40.180 --> 00:33:44.780
[Guest]: rural departments and urban departments looking at rural development and urban development

00:33:44.780 --> 00:33:51.340
[Guest]: separately. That's, I guess, that's, that's the reason why this happens. So that's, that's

00:33:51.340 --> 00:33:55.940
[Guest]: the second reason why you need to get definitions, right? Because you need to be able to if you

00:33:55.940 --> 00:34:00.300
[Guest]: if you're targeting is based on where a person lives, then you need to identify that place

00:34:00.300 --> 00:34:07.860
[Guest]: correctly. Now, why is the government not proactive in correcting the definitions? You

00:34:07.860 --> 00:34:12.500
[Guest]: know, if it is aware that there's a problem, then why is nothing being done about it? To

00:34:12.500 --> 00:34:20.540
[Guest]: that the answer sort of depends, it depends on the state governments. So in our constitution,

00:34:20.540 --> 00:34:27.020
[Guest]: local governments are under the state list. So the state that has to set out the rules

00:34:27.020 --> 00:34:33.300
[Guest]: to identify urban local bodies, the center can give broad guidelines, but the states

00:34:33.300 --> 00:34:38.580
[Guest]: have their own municipal acts for identifying urban local bodies. And there's political

00:34:38.580 --> 00:34:44.660
[Guest]: reasons sometimes for the states not to notify a town, even if it is, you know, has all urban

00:34:44.660 --> 00:34:50.860
[Guest]: like features. There's also pressure from the ground up at times. So it's not just that

00:34:50.860 --> 00:34:56.500
[Guest]: the state is at fault, there are at times demands from the citizens to not be classified

00:34:56.500 --> 00:35:01.260
[Guest]: from a rural to urban area, just as there are demands from the citizens. There have

00:35:01.260 --> 00:35:06.940
[Guest]: been historic demands from the citizens to actually be called a city, you know, because

00:35:06.940 --> 00:35:12.820
[Guest]: they think that they have the necessary numbers and the economic base to be done. So there's

00:35:12.820 --> 00:35:21.620
[Guest]: again, there's three reasons why. So the citizens will resist any conversion, if it means that

00:35:21.620 --> 00:35:26.420
[Guest]: they will lose out on the rural schemes, right? If you become urban, and if you no longer

00:35:26.420 --> 00:35:35.340
[Guest]: get NREGA or PMG-SY, these other things, then your incentives are not to become urban. Businesses

00:35:35.340 --> 00:35:43.180
[Guest]: sometimes also resist, so local businesses, because if they switch, then they may be subjected

00:35:43.180 --> 00:35:47.700
[Guest]: to higher taxation, they may be subjected to higher rents, you know, just the cost of

00:35:47.700 --> 00:35:52.980
[Guest]: doing business may go up, as opposed to being in a village where the regulations are a bit

00:35:52.980 --> 00:35:59.060
[Guest]: different. This tax thing also applies to villagers, because cities are typically levy

00:35:59.060 --> 00:36:04.420
[Guest]: property taxes. So if you're a, you know, a village, then the households don't need

00:36:04.420 --> 00:36:10.620
[Guest]: to pay a property tax. So these are the factors that can cause some resistance. And there's

00:36:10.620 --> 00:36:15.940
[Guest]: one more factor, which is the panchayat leaders themselves. So historically, some states have

00:36:15.940 --> 00:36:22.980
[Guest]: done very well in, in terms of the democratic decentralization of within the panchayati

00:36:22.980 --> 00:36:28.500
[Guest]: raj system, right? You have very strong elections, and you know, very well entrenched political

00:36:28.500 --> 00:36:33.780
[Guest]: parties, and so on, and leaders within the village. If there's a fear that the village

00:36:33.780 --> 00:36:40.180
[Guest]: gets either amalgamated into a larger town nearby, or if it gets converted into an urban

00:36:40.180 --> 00:36:46.020
[Guest]: area, it's a very different electoral system. So in cities, you have mayors, mayors have

00:36:46.020 --> 00:36:51.740
[Guest]: no real powers as compared to a sarpanch, right? A mayor is typically indirectly elected,

00:36:51.740 --> 00:36:56.820
[Guest]: typically not even for the same duration as his or her government would be. So that's

00:36:56.820 --> 00:37:02.180
[Guest]: the reason why say, political leaders would resist. But at the same time, there are countervailing

00:37:02.180 --> 00:37:06.460
[Guest]: factors also, as I mentioned, there have been people who fought to be within the city because

00:37:06.460 --> 00:37:11.980
[Guest]: they've realized that there are costs to having haphazard construction in their villages,

00:37:11.980 --> 00:37:15.820
[Guest]: which lead to building collapse, and so on. And, and, you know, they would like to get

00:37:15.820 --> 00:37:21.820
[Guest]: certain facilities, like, say, a big municipal hospital or some, some other amenities that

00:37:21.820 --> 00:37:28.060
[Guest]: say, a municipal body will be able to provide them. So it's not that it just goes one way.

00:37:28.060 --> 00:37:33.900
[Guest]: And you don't know, ultimately, like, which force ends up winning. But these are the different

00:37:33.900 --> 00:37:41.500
[Guest]: contestations that take place in in sort of determining an urban or a rural status. Yeah,

00:37:41.500 --> 00:37:47.900
[Guest]: and it differs, I mean, greatly from state. So we've seen that, for instance, West Bengal

00:37:47.900 --> 00:37:53.780
[Guest]: and Kerala tend to have very few urban local body. And, I mean, this is just a hypothesis,

00:37:53.780 --> 00:37:58.180
[Guest]: I was just thinking about it, it could be because they have a very, very strong tradition

00:37:58.180 --> 00:38:05.220
[Guest]: of decentralization and decentralized government. And so the, so I guess that there's a lot

00:38:05.220 --> 00:38:13.500
[Guest]: of power at the local levels to sort of resist conversion or sort of get the states to agree

00:38:13.500 --> 00:38:19.620
[Guest]: to not convert them. So these are also areas where a lot of the new urbanization that's

00:38:19.620 --> 00:38:23.980
[Guest]: coming up, they're not come under an urban local body, it's, it's either classified as

00:38:23.980 --> 00:38:29.660
[Guest]: urban by the census, but all it is sort of, they're just large settlements that continue

00:38:29.660 --> 00:38:32.940
[Amit Varma]: to be called villages.

00:38:32.940 --> 00:38:37.220
[Amit Varma]: It's so fascinating, and almost surreal that, you know, little things like definitions can

00:38:37.220 --> 00:38:43.900
[Amit Varma]: make such a huge difference in outcomes and in the lives of actual people, you know, before

00:38:43.900 --> 00:38:49.220
[Amit Varma]: I kind of proceed, I think, you know, just for our listeners, I should, you know, quickly

00:38:49.220 --> 00:38:52.780
[Amit Varma]: explain what I think is a common premise to both of us, which is that cities are a damn

00:38:52.780 --> 00:38:57.020
[Amit Varma]: good thing, urbanization is fantastic, we should continue to urbanize. Very briefly,

00:38:57.020 --> 00:39:02.940
[Amit Varma]: the reasons for this include, of course, that, you know, we denser, higher population density

00:39:02.940 --> 00:39:09.160
[Amit Varma]: means, you know, bigger economic networks, which we can access vastly more opportunities,

00:39:09.160 --> 00:39:13.020
[Amit Varma]: and so on and so forth, which is why, you know, however much people bemoan cities, it

00:39:13.020 --> 00:39:17.540
[Amit Varma]: is generally people living in cities who bemoan them as they live in cities. You know, the

00:39:17.540 --> 00:39:22.080
[Amit Varma]: bottom line is that so many people voluntarily come to a city and their revealed preference

00:39:22.080 --> 00:39:26.900
[Amit Varma]: tells you something about why that is. Also, from the point of view of the environment,

00:39:26.900 --> 00:39:31.620
[Amit Varma]: cities are a great thing, because cities allow you allow the state to say provide things

00:39:31.620 --> 00:39:38.660
[Amit Varma]: like water and electricity and so on, to people at a far lower per capita cost than would

00:39:38.660 --> 00:39:42.580
[Amit Varma]: otherwise be the case. Now, obviously, there are a lot of ways in which Indian city could

00:39:42.580 --> 00:39:48.380
[Amit Varma]: be optimized better, like if they were higher, if they, you know, reclaim the sky in the

00:39:48.380 --> 00:39:54.660
[Amit Varma]: phrase of Alex Tabarrok, our mutual friend, and all of that. And, you know, I'm going

00:39:54.660 --> 00:39:59.140
[Amit Varma]: to turn now to what I would call the pandemic paradox, which is that the, you know, the

00:39:59.140 --> 00:40:05.540
[Amit Varma]: pandemic, you know, inverts some of these processes in the sense that while otherwise

00:40:05.540 --> 00:40:10.260
[Amit Varma]: population density is such a fantastic and desirable thing, desirable, because it forms

00:40:10.260 --> 00:40:15.540
[Amit Varma]: in the first place, because it's desirable, because people are voluntarily moving to cities,

00:40:15.540 --> 00:40:20.460
[Amit Varma]: but in a pandemic is the other way around. In a pandemic, it's literally fatal. Tell

00:40:20.460 --> 00:40:26.660
[Amit Varma]: me a little bit about how sort of pandemics of the past have, you know, affected cities

00:40:26.660 --> 00:40:31.820
[Amit Varma]: like you've, you've written about this yourself about, you know, how, you know, the plague

00:40:31.820 --> 00:40:38.940
[Amit Varma]: changed Athens forever in 430 BC, Pericles died, among others, a century later, Constantinople,

00:40:38.940 --> 00:40:44.300
[Amit Varma]: and cities have always sort of had a tough time with pandemics, like you said, the third

00:40:44.300 --> 00:40:50.540
[Amit Varma]: risk of that you pointed out, which is contagion, you know, so how has that gone in the past?

00:40:50.540 --> 00:40:55.580
[Amit Varma]: And the thing is, cities have always rebounded, because people have always assumed that, okay,

00:40:55.580 --> 00:41:00.420
[Amit Varma]: there are trade offs, that there is a risk to going to cities like, you know, like you've

00:41:00.420 --> 00:41:05.220
[Amit Varma]: pointed out, you know, in the 19th century, the mortality rate in the life expectancy

00:41:05.220 --> 00:41:09.900
[Amit Varma]: in cities was actually less in rural areas, sometimes by as much as six, seven years,

00:41:09.900 --> 00:41:14.020
[Amit Varma]: because there were hubs of disease, there was no concept of public health, you know,

00:41:14.020 --> 00:41:18.140
[Amit Varma]: people had wrong notions, there was a point in time where people didn't even realize that,

00:41:18.140 --> 00:41:22.620
[Amit Varma]: you know, open water and open drainage can, you know, lead to diseases like cholera and

00:41:22.620 --> 00:41:27.820
[Amit Varma]: whatever, which is why the life expectancy was lower, but people still, you know, realizing

00:41:27.820 --> 00:41:32.580
[Amit Varma]: the trade off of this still chose to go to cities, because the opportunities were just

00:41:32.580 --> 00:41:39.220
[Amit Varma]: way, way greater. So give me a sense of how through history, what's been the relationship

00:41:39.220 --> 00:41:44.540
[Amit Varma]: between, you know, cities and pandemics and how people think about both? Yeah, I think

00:41:44.540 --> 00:41:51.260
[Guest]: there was an interesting example that Ed Glazer gave when he said, an Irishman, you know,

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:59.300
[Guest]: back in the day, would rather, you know, choose the likelihood of giving, getting cholera

00:41:59.300 --> 00:42:08.780
[Guest]: moving to a city over like being subjected to the say, the potato famines. So it's never

00:42:08.780 --> 00:42:15.260
[Guest]: been a very easy trade off, you were essentially choosing the lesser of the two years, and

00:42:15.260 --> 00:42:21.180
[Guest]: anything that increased your chances of survival, it's it, it was, it was quite bleak in, back

00:42:21.180 --> 00:42:31.260
[Guest]: in the 19th centuries. And several examples of, of large epidemics, breaking out and claiming

00:42:31.260 --> 00:42:38.260
[Guest]: millions of lives exist. Starting, I mean, of course, with the cholera epidemics in London,

00:42:38.260 --> 00:42:43.820
[Guest]: New York City also had yellow fever epidemics, cholera epidemics. In Mumbai, we also had

00:42:43.820 --> 00:42:49.020
[Guest]: bubonic plagues in the late 1800s. So our Epidemic Diseases Act actually comes from

00:42:49.020 --> 00:42:55.460
[Guest]: there. It comes from the bubonic plague in Bombay. And, and what was done, I mean, the

00:42:55.460 --> 00:43:03.620
[Guest]: act was then created in order to help the like rulers tackle the pandemic. So it's been

00:43:03.620 --> 00:43:11.300
[Guest]: a feature, I mean, a bug rather, of our cities, that we had, because of the invention of germ

00:43:11.300 --> 00:43:18.660
[Guest]: theory, because of very, very massive investments in public health infrastructure, managed to

00:43:18.660 --> 00:43:25.620
[Guest]: keep at bay. So that's how we, we saw these kind of large scale epidemics getting fewer

00:43:25.620 --> 00:43:31.380
[Guest]: and farther in between. And whenever they cropped up, there was easier ways to tackle

00:43:31.380 --> 00:43:35.740
[Guest]: them. You know, people knew enough, there was enough for vaccines and all these scientific

00:43:35.740 --> 00:43:41.820
[Guest]: advancements that helped you live in the city. So that sort of that bleak choice that existed

00:43:41.820 --> 00:43:46.820
[Guest]: earlier no longer was the case. So it sort of attracted more people. We also see this

00:43:46.820 --> 00:43:52.980
[Guest]: as a time like the early 20th century is a time when the city started growing in size.

00:43:52.980 --> 00:43:58.340
[Guest]: Because the cities in those days were much larger than the cities in the previous centuries,

00:43:58.340 --> 00:44:04.020
[Guest]: because you'd solve for these, you know, very grim problems. So the ways in which you can

00:44:04.020 --> 00:44:10.300
[Guest]: solve them exist, and they continue to exist. But I think what also started happening was

00:44:10.300 --> 00:44:17.620
[Guest]: in the 1960s onward, the more the urbanization sort of the stage for the next phase of urbanization

00:44:17.620 --> 00:44:22.980
[Guest]: shifted from these very developed countries to the developing world, which has not yet

00:44:22.980 --> 00:44:27.460
[Guest]: I mean, we know what's to be done, we know that you need to make investments in clean

00:44:27.460 --> 00:44:34.060
[Guest]: water, sanitation, and so on. But for various state capacity reasons, maybe even, you know,

00:44:34.060 --> 00:44:38.900
[Guest]: the type of government that you have, these are not either policy priorities, or they're

00:44:38.900 --> 00:44:44.300
[Guest]: just not being well implemented. For these reasons, when this next stage of urbanization

00:44:44.300 --> 00:44:52.300
[Guest]: kicked off in the developing countries, this sort of problem has sort of emerged as, again,

00:44:52.300 --> 00:45:02.780
[Guest]: one of the ugly facets of urbanization. And the pandemic was honestly something that was,

00:45:02.780 --> 00:45:08.060
[Guest]: it's affected all countries, of course, it's affected the cities much harder, even the

00:45:08.060 --> 00:45:13.380
[Guest]: cities in developed countries, simply because of the nature of the densities that we've

00:45:13.380 --> 00:45:19.140
[Guest]: we've talked about. But what's different this time around is, of course, we have a lot more

00:45:19.140 --> 00:45:24.580
[Guest]: scientific advancement, we know what has to be done, it's just a matter of time, as they

00:45:24.580 --> 00:45:28.740
[Guest]: say, before vaccines are coming up. It's not that everyone's just, you know, put out put

00:45:28.740 --> 00:45:35.180
[Guest]: up their hands and is waiting for death or some situation like that. We are all waiting

00:45:35.180 --> 00:45:44.540
[Guest]: for death. Well, hopefully for death at some point later, not death due to pandemic. But

00:45:44.540 --> 00:45:52.660
[Guest]: what's happened is, we, because in the developing world, the cities have just become too large,

00:45:52.660 --> 00:46:00.940
[Guest]: and too badly managed, we are just going to end up having major disasters. I don't know

00:46:00.940 --> 00:46:07.140
[Guest]: how I don't know what has happened with we've come far along enough in the pandemic, and

00:46:07.140 --> 00:46:13.860
[Guest]: it's not yet like had a very, very bad impact on say, the large cities in Africa, large

00:46:13.860 --> 00:46:19.420
[Guest]: cities in in other parts of Asia. And I mean, I don't know, like what that causes, maybe

00:46:19.420 --> 00:46:23.900
[Guest]: we'll know a few years later, whether it was a different strain or what, but certainly

00:46:23.900 --> 00:46:30.900
[Guest]: if the same level of impact that that hit cities in the developing world, a developed

00:46:30.900 --> 00:46:37.260
[Guest]: world had hit the developing world, we would have been seeing large scale sort of devastation

00:46:37.260 --> 00:46:44.660
[Guest]: and completely crumbling and broken down infrastructure of all kinds. And we do end up, I mean, in

00:46:44.660 --> 00:46:51.100
[Guest]: Mumbai, in the cities in India, where things have, I mean, where the pandemic has hit very

00:46:51.100 --> 00:46:57.300
[Guest]: hard, you have seen the city infrastructure struggle. So in this instance, I think the

00:46:57.300 --> 00:47:04.940
[Guest]: reason why we've not been able to, even though the lockdown was supposed to allow us to build

00:47:04.940 --> 00:47:11.900
[Guest]: up our infrastructure, we were not very able to do that, perhaps because we don't have

00:47:11.900 --> 00:47:17.740
[Guest]: systems in place that, you know, or sort of institutions in place that actually plan for

00:47:17.740 --> 00:47:24.540
[Guest]: these. Well, we don't have great surveillance systems, and wherever they do exist, they,

00:47:24.540 --> 00:47:29.340
[Guest]: you know, say, like Kerala will come out as one of them. And that's also because it had

00:47:29.340 --> 00:47:35.260
[Guest]: to deal with, say, a Nipah a few years ago. So it's our entire sort of urban public health

00:47:35.260 --> 00:47:41.500
[Guest]: infrastructure and our, which is just healthcare infrastructure, has been geared towards sort

00:47:41.500 --> 00:47:47.220
[Guest]: of very limited types of things to do. We don't have in our cities, even though it should

00:47:47.220 --> 00:47:54.300
[Guest]: be possible to have, we don't have, you know, disaster planning for like, infectious diseases,

00:47:54.300 --> 00:48:01.940
[Guest]: we don't have any sort of infrastructure that does that. And that sort of thinking at an

00:48:01.940 --> 00:48:10.780
[Guest]: institutional level is what is a, has sort of let things get made things get worse. The

00:48:10.780 --> 00:48:19.900
[Guest]: third thing is, we don't look at public health infrastructure as a, you know, as a public

00:48:19.900 --> 00:48:25.340
[Guest]: health problem. So we don't look at, I mean, we look at water and sanitation and public

00:48:25.340 --> 00:48:32.340
[Guest]: solid waste management, as very, very, like in silos. And so, okay, we know that if you,

00:48:32.340 --> 00:48:36.940
[Guest]: of course, we know the benefits of providing clean water, we know the benefits of, of providing

00:48:36.940 --> 00:48:42.980
[Guest]: sanitation, and the, you know, the impact it has on cholera related, typhoid related

00:48:42.980 --> 00:48:48.660
[Guest]: deaths, diarrhea related deaths, and all of that is known. But we don't look at all of

00:48:48.660 --> 00:48:56.820
[Guest]: this together as something that is important for the city in terms of, from a health perspective,

00:48:56.820 --> 00:49:03.420
[Guest]: we look at it from a service provision perspective. I think that's what's ended up happening where

00:49:03.420 --> 00:49:07.860
[Guest]: we have different departments doing different things without any common sort of objective

00:49:07.860 --> 00:49:14.020
[Guest]: of public health and public health includes like, and these three things get subsumed

00:49:14.020 --> 00:49:18.780
[Guest]: under public health, right? We have a separate, we have the silo based way of functioning,

00:49:18.780 --> 00:49:24.820
[Guest]: which is, in my opinion, led to some problems that we face and this inability to have a

00:49:24.820 --> 00:49:27.900
[Guest]: coordinated way of dealing with diseases.

00:49:27.900 --> 00:49:33.820
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, that's been a perpetual problem in urban governance that we function in these

00:49:33.820 --> 00:49:38.620
[Amit Varma]: silos. I'll come back to that later. And also to the question of, you know, how cities both

00:49:38.620 --> 00:49:43.700
[Amit Varma]: here and across the world have sort of been affected by COVID. But before that, just to

00:49:43.700 --> 00:49:50.100
[Amit Varma]: take a step back, I have like a two part question, which is, you know, you referred to how that

00:49:50.100 --> 00:49:54.860
[Amit Varma]: trade off between, you know, cities being so dangerous, and should we go to cities and

00:49:54.860 --> 00:49:59.500
[Amit Varma]: get the economic benefits and the social benefits even of being in cities, how that changed

00:49:59.500 --> 00:50:03.580
[Amit Varma]: completely when cities just became much better places to live. And one reason for that, as

00:50:03.580 --> 00:50:07.700
[Amit Varma]: you point pointed out was just the growth of knowledge and technology, like you understood

00:50:07.700 --> 00:50:12.980
[Amit Varma]: germ theory. And, you know, your technology advanced to the point where you could cure

00:50:12.980 --> 00:50:16.820
[Amit Varma]: what would otherwise be severe diseases very quickly, and blah, blah, blah. So that's the

00:50:16.820 --> 00:50:22.740
[Amit Varma]: technology part of it. But in terms of governance, you know, what were the things that were done,

00:50:22.740 --> 00:50:28.460
[Amit Varma]: which mitigated the impact of cities, you know, that part of the impact of cities where

00:50:28.460 --> 00:50:33.140
[Amit Varma]: they became more livable? And the second part of the question is that, did governments did

00:50:33.140 --> 00:50:39.060
[Amit Varma]: the state over a period of time get complacent about the possible ill effects of contagion?

00:50:39.060 --> 00:50:44.220
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, they had, you know, your technology had advanced enough that, you know,

00:50:44.220 --> 00:50:48.020
[Amit Varma]: pandemics weren't breaking out all the time and things seemed okay, did they get complacent?

00:50:48.020 --> 00:50:52.740
[Amit Varma]: And is that something that, you know, they will begin to, they are beginning to rethink

00:50:52.740 --> 00:50:54.540
[Guest]: now, you think?

00:50:54.540 --> 00:51:02.980
[Guest]: So the first thing about what changed in terms of governance, my sense is that the governance

00:51:02.980 --> 00:51:10.940
[Guest]: did not change. It was the priorities of existing governments that, within cities that changed,

00:51:10.940 --> 00:51:16.020
[Guest]: because they realized that, you know, we need to keep the rich in the city, we need their

00:51:16.020 --> 00:51:22.660
[Guest]: tax money, let's, you know, ensure a clean environment, and clean, you know, water and

00:51:22.660 --> 00:51:29.460
[Guest]: so on for them, we need businesses to stay. So that was that realization that led to sort

00:51:29.460 --> 00:51:35.940
[Guest]: of setting up of these, you know, specialized public health departments or public health

00:51:35.940 --> 00:51:42.460
[Guest]: boards that did a lot of surveillance work that planned for where the public health infrastructure

00:51:42.460 --> 00:51:47.660
[Guest]: will be, how to bring clean water in from outside the city, you know, through the aqueducts

00:51:47.660 --> 00:51:54.660
[Guest]: and so on. So all of that was sort of done through this special, I think, Bombay also

00:51:54.660 --> 00:51:59.540
[Guest]: had that in the Bombay Improvement Trust. So the context was different, of course, you

00:51:59.540 --> 00:52:06.420
[Guest]: had the British elite living in, you know, certain part of the city, and they, the BIT,

00:52:06.420 --> 00:52:12.020
[Guest]: of course, first made sure that those areas are, you know, were prioritized in terms of

00:52:12.020 --> 00:52:18.580
[Guest]: ensuring that you have clean sanitation and clean water being provided. And then there

00:52:18.580 --> 00:52:24.740
[Guest]: was later on, it was expanded to outside of the, of the colonies, where the working classes

00:52:24.740 --> 00:52:29.620
[Guest]: live, only because they realized that, you know, if, if there is any outbreak in these,

00:52:29.620 --> 00:52:35.820
[Guest]: you know, very, very dense quarters of weather, where the subjects lived, then it's going

00:52:35.820 --> 00:52:41.460
[Guest]: to quickly come into their colonies and affect them. So there was some effort that was done

00:52:41.460 --> 00:52:49.300
[Guest]: to widen the roads in the areas where the working classes and the, you know, the Indian

00:52:49.300 --> 00:52:57.180
[Guest]: parts of the city. So it came from this incentive, it was about like ensuring the, because these

00:52:57.180 --> 00:53:03.340
[Guest]: cities were so economically important to the either the government or the colonial powers

00:53:03.340 --> 00:53:07.660
[Guest]: in the case of India, that in terms of the trade and the commerce that they brought in

00:53:07.660 --> 00:53:13.180
[Guest]: in terms of the tax dollars, that they brought in that it was a natural priority to try and

00:53:13.180 --> 00:53:18.180
[Guest]: make sure that they continue to dominate in the trade and commerce in the, in the world.

00:53:18.180 --> 00:53:26.180
[Guest]: Those sort of incentives don't exist as much. I mean, in today's day and age, there's a

00:53:26.180 --> 00:53:32.900
[Guest]: lot of, if you look at it different, if you look at the developing countries, this sort

00:53:32.900 --> 00:53:39.460
[Guest]: of incentive does not exist as much because the people who should be concerned about Mumbai's

00:53:39.460 --> 00:53:45.340
[Guest]: primacy as a global city don't live in Mumbai, you know, the tax dollars that come to Mumbai

00:53:45.340 --> 00:53:51.540
[Guest]: are not invested in Mumbai, they go to all other parts. So there's a lot of different

00:53:51.540 --> 00:53:57.380
[Guest]: political economy reasons. And I think, I mean, I can talk a little bit about this,

00:53:57.380 --> 00:54:01.980
[Guest]: if you want, but there's this thing about that we don't have a decentralized system,

00:54:01.980 --> 00:54:08.460
[Guest]: right? You don't have a powerful city leader, who has a vested interest in keeping the city

00:54:08.460 --> 00:54:17.420
[Guest]: prosperous, because that would lead to that, you know, him and his government or getting

00:54:17.420 --> 00:54:22.780
[Guest]: more revenues, and then you know, that they can invest in and get elected, you know, and

00:54:22.780 --> 00:54:27.500
[Guest]: claim that this is what they've done for the city and therefore get elected. So these sort

00:54:27.500 --> 00:54:34.340
[Guest]: of electoral incentives are completely broken. And so you don't see, you know, this natural

00:54:34.340 --> 00:54:40.740
[Guest]: priority of any city leadership, to make sure that the cities are healthy, is not there

00:54:40.740 --> 00:54:45.540
[Guest]: because of these broken electoral incentives, in my opinion.

00:54:45.540 --> 00:54:51.420
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I'd done an episode with Shruti, I think in 2017, or two and a half years ago, where

00:54:51.420 --> 00:54:56.500
[Amit Varma]: we spoke about this aspect of urban governance, you know, especially in the context of Maharashtra

00:54:56.500 --> 00:55:01.580
[Amit Varma]: where, you know, power and accountability are de-linked here. So the people who are

00:55:01.580 --> 00:55:06.140
[Amit Varma]: accountable to voters in Mumbai, or local councillors and whatever, have no power to

00:55:06.140 --> 00:55:10.020
[Amit Varma]: make these big decisions. And the people who do have the power in the state government,

00:55:10.020 --> 00:55:13.900
[Amit Varma]: the votes that they're chasing are elsewhere, and they don't really care about the city.

00:55:13.900 --> 00:55:20.460
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, you want, you know, sort of governance to be as local as possible. So,

00:55:20.460 --> 00:55:25.780
[Amit Varma]: you know, we don't, so there's a more direct link between, you know, performance and all

00:55:25.780 --> 00:55:30.020
[Amit Varma]: of that. So, you know, we'll take a quick commercial break now. And then when we come

00:55:30.020 --> 00:55:37.860
[Amit Varma]: back, we'll get right down to the subject at hand, which is COVID and our cities.

00:55:37.860 --> 00:55:42.300
[Amit Varma]: On the scene and the unseen, I often speak about positive sum games. Well, if you want

00:55:42.300 --> 00:55:47.140
