[Amit Varma]: to do so. And you know, this is fascinating piece that Ruben and you wrote a few weeks

00:57:03.340 --> 00:57:08.140
[Amit Varma]: ago. And I just want to quote from there because I kind of find this fascinating where you're

00:57:08.140 --> 00:57:14.260
[Amit Varma]: talking about how, where some cities were less affected than other cities. And quote,

00:57:14.260 --> 00:57:19.620
[Amit Varma]: sold with a population density of 16,000 persons per square kilometer, had far fewer cases

00:57:19.620 --> 00:57:24.220
[Amit Varma]: in New York. Taipei, whose density is comparable to New York, did not suffer from a serious

00:57:24.220 --> 00:57:29.300
[Amit Varma]: outbreak. Other Asian mega cities such as Hanoi, Hong Kong and Bangkok have done well

00:57:29.300 --> 00:57:33.580
[Amit Varma]: too. A World Bank study of the outbreak in China shows that population densities in cities

00:57:33.580 --> 00:57:38.500
[Amit Varma]: are not correlated to the spread of the virus. Very dense cities such as Beijing, Shanghai

00:57:38.500 --> 00:57:44.260
[Amit Varma]: and Tianjin have remained relatively unscathed. Stop quote and apologies if I've, you know,

00:57:44.260 --> 00:57:49.340
[Amit Varma]: mispronounced the name of one or more of the Chinese cities. So my question is, you know,

00:57:49.340 --> 00:57:53.780
[Amit Varma]: one reason, of course, why Southeast Asia dealt with this pandemic better is because

00:57:53.780 --> 00:57:58.740
[Amit Varma]: they had experience of previous pandemics. So they could reflexively move into social

00:57:58.740 --> 00:58:04.060
[Amit Varma]: distancing mode and it is common there to wear a mask anyway. And, you know, all of

00:58:04.060 --> 00:58:09.180
[Amit Varma]: those little normative things help. But from the point of view of what you've studied,

00:58:09.180 --> 00:58:13.620
[Amit Varma]: the way cities are governed and so on, like, why do you think there is such a vast difference

00:58:13.620 --> 00:58:18.260
[Amit Varma]: between because the assumption is that where the density is greater, the spread of COVID

00:58:18.260 --> 00:58:22.380
[Amit Varma]: will be higher. But that's not really borne out by the data. Clearly, there are other

00:58:22.380 --> 00:58:26.580
[Amit Varma]: things at play as well. So tell me a little bit about your insights into this.

00:58:26.580 --> 00:58:34.020
[Guest]: Yeah, so this was actually largely a piece that came out of, you know, this panic almost

00:58:34.020 --> 00:58:41.500
[Guest]: among people that, you know, densities are bad. And there's cities are obviously the

00:58:41.500 --> 00:58:52.260
[Guest]: villains and we need to focus on rural development. So it came from the fact that there is not

00:58:52.260 --> 00:58:58.180
[Guest]: there needs to be a more nuanced understanding of what densities are. And if this was the

00:58:58.180 --> 00:59:05.460
[Guest]: case, why do we not see the most dense parts of the cities, even within cities, the most

00:59:05.460 --> 00:59:14.940
[Guest]: dense areas not experiencing high outbreaks. And we realize that it is, of course, the

00:59:14.940 --> 00:59:21.580
[Guest]: fact that I mean, one pattern is that if any city has in the recent past had to deal with

00:59:21.580 --> 00:59:27.900
[Guest]: an epidemic or a flu like or a SARS like epidemic, they've had the infrastructure in place to

00:59:27.900 --> 00:59:33.700
[Guest]: allow like immediate surveillance and, and shutting down and so on and without even actually

00:59:33.700 --> 00:59:39.060
[Guest]: going to the drastic step of shutting down and locking down all economic activity even

00:59:39.060 --> 00:59:49.620
[Guest]: without doing that have been able to manage this. But we find that in the case of, say,

00:59:49.620 --> 00:59:55.540
[Guest]: if you look in Mumbai, and you look at densities across different boards, you're not going

00:59:55.540 --> 01:00:03.940
[Guest]: to find the most dense area seeing the outbreaks, you're going to find, perhaps the most, the

01:00:03.940 --> 01:00:12.100
[Guest]: areas that are most deficient in amenities, like clean water in terms of, you know, pipe

01:00:12.100 --> 01:00:20.100
[Guest]: water in and then also sanitation in terms of having proper indoor toilets, those areas

01:00:20.100 --> 01:00:27.380
[Guest]: you're going to see are going to be worst hit. And this was also shown in a recent study

01:00:27.380 --> 01:00:37.980
[Guest]: of a CEROS survey that was done by Anup Malani and a bunch of others along with, I think

01:00:37.980 --> 01:00:44.900
[Guest]: TIFR, there were scientists there and that those results made a big, you know, like they

01:00:44.900 --> 01:00:51.700
[Guest]: made it to the front pages of a lot of papers which showed that slum areas tended to have

01:00:51.700 --> 01:00:59.700
[Guest]: a lot higher seroprevalence compared to non-slum areas. We can't conflate slum and non-slum

01:00:59.700 --> 01:01:07.380
[Guest]: with more dense and less dense. Because you, you may be living in a dense area, but it

01:01:07.380 --> 01:01:12.220
[Guest]: what matters is what is the consumption of floor space that you have? What is, you know,

01:01:12.220 --> 01:01:17.420
[Guest]: it's about indoor crowding. If I'm living, you know, if there are a hundred people living

01:01:17.420 --> 01:01:23.380
[Guest]: in a building, but I mean, you're living in an area as opposed to a thousand people living

01:01:23.380 --> 01:01:30.540
[Guest]: in another area, but the per capita space available to those living in the hundred population

01:01:30.540 --> 01:01:35.740
[Guest]: neighborhood is less than the per capita space available to the ones that are living in a

01:01:35.740 --> 01:01:42.300
[Guest]: thousand population neighborhood, then we cannot say that, that it's densities that

01:01:42.300 --> 01:01:48.220
[Guest]: are at fault. It's the fact that you have not allowed, say, enough construction or you've

01:01:48.220 --> 01:01:55.020
[Guest]: not allowed enough floor space, you've not had enough housing to be built, which is leading

01:01:55.020 --> 01:01:59.820
[Guest]: to people cramming indoors as opposed to, you know, just looking at densities. What

01:01:59.820 --> 01:02:04.740
[Guest]: is an important metric to look at is indoor crowding. And if you ask why indoor crowding

01:02:04.740 --> 01:02:11.660
[Guest]: is happening, you will come back to that same question of, you know, why is there not more

01:02:11.660 --> 01:02:17.100
[Guest]: construction for the poor? Like, and that leads you to the question of, again, your

01:02:17.100 --> 01:02:27.700
[Guest]: whole set of land use constraints that stop people from building more. And that the motivation

01:02:27.700 --> 01:02:33.300
[Guest]: for these laws and these regulations of stopping construction, not allowing construction is

01:02:33.300 --> 01:02:40.980
[Guest]: ironically a fear of densities. So it's this strange sort of situation where you're blaming

01:02:40.980 --> 01:02:47.740
[Guest]: densities, but what's the real culprit is not densities, it's not having enough housing

01:02:47.740 --> 01:02:53.380
[Guest]: per capita or not having enough housing space per capita. That's the issue.

01:02:53.380 --> 01:02:58.780
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's so ironic, and it fits exactly into the framework of the seen and the unseen,

01:02:58.780 --> 01:03:04.380
[Amit Varma]: that your intended effect for all these regulations is that let's do away with density, and your

01:03:04.380 --> 01:03:09.100
[Amit Varma]: unintended consequences that it's leading to density because you have 15 people cramped

01:03:09.100 --> 01:03:14.700
[Amit Varma]: in a crowd, you know, in a small room, because, you know, there's this artificial scarcity

01:03:14.700 --> 01:03:19.820
[Amit Varma]: created by bad laws and regulation, in a sense does, you know, like people often say that

01:03:19.820 --> 01:03:26.300
[Amit Varma]: a crisis is a good time for reform. And one of the things that this crisis does seem to

01:03:26.300 --> 01:03:33.300
[Amit Varma]: have done is pointed out the importance even the urgency of reforms that otherwise people

01:03:33.300 --> 01:03:39.860
[Amit Varma]: like, you know, you and me have been writing about for donkey's years, such as, for example,

01:03:39.860 --> 01:03:44.580
[Amit Varma]: just FSI reform, where you have, you know, in Alex's words, again, if Mumbai reclaimed

01:03:44.580 --> 01:03:49.980
[Amit Varma]: the sky instead of the sea, and it just grew upwards, you'd have less of these 15 people

01:03:49.980 --> 01:03:54.780
[Amit Varma]: trapped in a room, you'd have land, which was much more affordable, infrastructure would

01:03:54.780 --> 01:03:59.740
[Amit Varma]: keep up with all of this, there would even be more revenues for city governments, though

01:03:59.740 --> 01:04:05.500
[Amit Varma]: the Mumbai city government has so much unused revenue that that's hardly an issue. So is

01:04:05.500 --> 01:04:10.100
[Amit Varma]: that something that so first of all, you know, when you talk to people within government,

01:04:10.100 --> 01:04:14.660
[Amit Varma]: and when you talk to policymakers, and you talk about say things like FSI or rent control,

01:04:14.660 --> 01:04:18.020
[Amit Varma]: and talk about how these are actually harming the poor, I mean, that's what they eventually

01:04:18.020 --> 01:04:24.180
[Amit Varma]: come down to, because you create scarcities of available land and places to live, prices

01:04:24.180 --> 01:04:29.020
[Amit Varma]: go up, it's a poor who suffer and then therefore have to live in these overcrowded slums, where

01:04:29.020 --> 01:04:33.780
[Amit Varma]: they are far more vulnerable to contagion. So first of all, even before COVID, was there

01:04:33.780 --> 01:04:38.260
[Amit Varma]: a recognition that these are problems? Or would they just indulge you as you spoke about

01:04:38.260 --> 01:04:43.260
[Amit Varma]: this stuff? And, you know, they weren't incentivized to do anything about it. And whatever the

01:04:43.260 --> 01:04:49.420
[Amit Varma]: answer to that is that would that have changed in any direction? Now, because fixes like

01:04:49.420 --> 01:04:56.340
[Amit Varma]: these are powerful structural fixes that are however, long term fixes, you know, not short

01:04:56.340 --> 01:05:01.340
[Amit Varma]: term fixes. And my worry here as a citizen who's watched the Indian state closely at

01:05:01.340 --> 01:05:06.900
[Amit Varma]: work for decades is that a crisis will come and when the crisis is over, they'll forget

01:05:06.900 --> 01:05:11.700
[Amit Varma]: all about it and its business as usual. So what's your sense of sort of dealing with

01:05:11.700 --> 01:05:19.260
[Amit Varma]: policymakers on all of this? And do you think that change is likely to happen?

01:05:19.260 --> 01:05:28.420
[Guest]: So I'm reluctant to bunch all government people in the same, you know, same bucket, or all

01:05:28.420 --> 01:05:35.820
[Guest]: politicians in the same bucket. I think there are enough smart and motivated people in government

01:05:35.820 --> 01:05:42.660
[Guest]: who get things done, which is what makes some of the work we do exciting and relevant. Otherwise,

01:05:42.660 --> 01:05:47.660
[Guest]: you know, we would be better off just writing op-eds and, you know, instead of talking to

01:05:47.660 --> 01:05:54.180
[Guest]: people, instead of talking to government officials, and so on. So there are two ways in which

01:05:54.180 --> 01:06:01.460
[Guest]: this could go. There could be a set of people, powerful voices that say that, well, we've

01:06:01.460 --> 01:06:06.700
[Guest]: always pointed out that cities were bad. Now look, so why are you, you know, focusing on

01:06:06.700 --> 01:06:12.700
[Guest]: cities, focus on on the villages, let's keep the returning workers in the villages and

01:06:12.700 --> 01:06:17.140
[Guest]: provide them enough opportunities there. And you know, like, let them not face hardships

01:06:17.140 --> 01:06:21.580
[Guest]: and go into cities and, you know, see what look what happened to all of them. These cities

01:06:21.580 --> 01:06:27.500
[Guest]: just close their doors and so on. So there's one sort of political voices that would talk

01:06:27.500 --> 01:06:34.500
[Guest]: about this. I have, like, not seen at least in the public sphere and a counter voice to

01:06:34.500 --> 01:06:43.020
[Guest]: this politically. And that is what is a little disappointing. And that's what makes me pessimistic.

01:06:43.020 --> 01:06:50.220
[Guest]: I mean, I think I would know enough people, individual people who would, who are not like

01:06:50.220 --> 01:06:56.940
[Guest]: that, who are very, who are still, you know, very bullish on on cities. And, and we again,

01:06:56.940 --> 01:07:01.380
[Guest]: we're seeing the return, the workers coming back, right, like those who had gone away

01:07:01.380 --> 01:07:09.420
[Guest]: once the economy slowly, you know, came back, restarted. And so if people come back, resume

01:07:09.420 --> 01:07:15.180
[Guest]: their old jobs or look for new jobs and so on. So politically, I'm not seeing that sort

01:07:15.180 --> 01:07:22.020
[Guest]: of voice. And again, the incentives are different, completely political reasons why certain sides

01:07:22.020 --> 01:07:27.300
[Guest]: are being taken versus others. And that's, I think that's a failure to recognize people's

01:07:27.300 --> 01:07:34.180
[Guest]: aspirations. I think if you are, it's a to me a very misguided thing for you to believe

01:07:34.180 --> 01:07:40.820
[Guest]: that the people who returned will actually stay without trying to understand what their

01:07:40.820 --> 01:07:46.460
[Guest]: aspirations are, if their aspirations were to make something of themselves, or, you know,

01:07:46.460 --> 01:07:52.300
[Guest]: make sure that the children don't have to face the same hardships that they did, then

01:07:52.300 --> 01:07:58.300
[Guest]: the messaging would be very different. I feel I mean, or, I mean, I'm not saying that, in

01:07:58.300 --> 01:08:03.300
[Guest]: fact, I guess most, I know nothing about politics. So I shouldn't, I should not talk about what

01:08:03.300 --> 01:08:09.100
[Guest]: the how to win votes or what the what winning strategy in this case would be. But in my

01:08:09.100 --> 01:08:16.500
[Guest]: mind, it's just that it's a puzzle to me like, are these do these people like, are their

01:08:16.500 --> 01:08:22.660
[Guest]: aspirations not being understood? And like, if they were, then you would sort of be talking

01:08:22.660 --> 01:08:27.860
[Guest]: about some other things you would be talking about, you know, making sure that your cities

01:08:27.860 --> 01:08:35.220
[Guest]: are looking after, you know, the, the most vulnerable people and so on. We're seeing

01:08:35.220 --> 01:08:42.900
[Guest]: some of that conversation happen in the, you know, among the people and the organizations

01:08:42.900 --> 01:08:48.820
[Guest]: working in the development, the development sector. So the, you know, the World Banks

01:08:48.820 --> 01:08:55.420
[Guest]: and all your other multilateral organizations and some other sort of, I guess think tanks

01:08:55.420 --> 01:09:02.180
[Guest]: are also trying to think through, okay, let's, let's look at what the issues are with in

01:09:02.180 --> 01:09:07.780
[Guest]: terms of say, migrant housing in terms of access to social protection for the urban

01:09:07.780 --> 01:09:14.620
[Guest]: poor, and let's try and fix those systems. But ultimately, I mean, it's a political thing.

01:09:14.620 --> 01:09:19.740
[Guest]: And I don't, I don't know how it will end up happening, whether or not will end up happening

01:09:19.740 --> 01:09:27.860
[Guest]: despite so many people saying, or so many like non-political voices talking about, about

01:09:27.860 --> 01:09:34.020
[Guest]: these issues. And if I would just to sort of go a step further, it's also about who

01:09:34.020 --> 01:09:40.380
[Guest]: does the fiscal burden fall on, right? So if states where the cities are have to now

01:09:40.380 --> 01:09:46.020
[Guest]: be responsible for the people that are coming to work in their cities, that's an added fiscal

01:09:46.020 --> 01:09:51.980
[Guest]: burden without on the states, right? And that's something that I don't see states taking on

01:09:51.980 --> 01:09:57.780
[Guest]: very willingly, because these are not voters for them. Their World Banks are different.

01:09:57.780 --> 01:10:06.000
[Guest]: So these complicated political, you know, calculations make me a lot more pessimistic.

01:10:06.000 --> 01:10:10.580
[Guest]: It's not the intentions of people. I don't think, you know, politicians are necessarily

01:10:10.580 --> 01:10:16.820
[Guest]: anti-states or whatever, but they have their own reasons for posturing as being anti-city

01:10:16.820 --> 01:10:18.700
[Amit Varma]: and so on. Yeah.

01:10:18.700 --> 01:10:23.420
[Amit Varma]: And how much of governance happens below the surface of politics? For example, you know,

01:10:23.420 --> 01:10:29.060
[Amit Varma]: I would imagine a politician would be interested and deeply involved in all of the things that

01:10:29.060 --> 01:10:34.780
[Amit Varma]: can affect the optics of governance. But there are a lot of things in terms of daily governance,

01:10:34.780 --> 01:10:39.500
[Amit Varma]: which happened below the surface, which nobody really notices, which they have no incentive

01:10:39.500 --> 01:10:45.060
[Amit Varma]: to really care about one way or the other. So I guess there, the bureaucracy in the deep

01:10:45.060 --> 01:10:49.660
[Amit Varma]: state, as it were, sort of becomes much more relevant in terms of what is done and what

01:10:49.660 --> 01:10:55.460
[Amit Varma]: is not done. What's your experience of dealing with the bureaucracy in those kind of circumstances?

01:10:55.460 --> 01:11:04.500
[Guest]: Again, there are well-intentioned, but somewhat hamstrung by the kind of, you know, structures

01:11:04.500 --> 01:11:13.140
[Guest]: that they have put in place. So I've come across bureaucrats who want to do things and

01:11:13.140 --> 01:11:19.540
[Guest]: some of them have been able to push through things. I mean, I don't want to name names,

01:11:19.540 --> 01:11:24.860
[Guest]: but there have been cities like Pune, cities like Mumbai, cities like Chennai, I have seen

01:11:24.860 --> 01:11:31.780
[Guest]: bureaucrats who have been able to do things for the betterment of the city, whether it

01:11:31.780 --> 01:11:40.140
[Guest]: is pushing through reforms like, say, property tax systems and so on. So I think there is

01:11:40.140 --> 01:11:47.780
[Guest]: some hope at that stage. But again, if you look at the other compulsion or the, I mean,

01:11:47.780 --> 01:11:54.780
[Guest]: the other constraint there is that you need the person to be there at least for one entire

01:11:54.780 --> 01:12:00.860
[Guest]: political cycle, right? At least for five years for them to actually get the hang of

01:12:00.860 --> 01:12:05.100
[Guest]: the department and then figure out what the problems are, and then listen to people who

01:12:05.100 --> 01:12:11.140
[Guest]: have the solutions for it, and then, you know, make sure that things get, at least the ball

01:12:11.140 --> 01:12:17.860
[Guest]: gets rolling. And that's sort of like, that's not, that's a luxury in the administrative

01:12:17.860 --> 01:12:26.300
[Guest]: services, actually. So if you have bureaucrats who've spent enough time, say, as urban managers

01:12:26.300 --> 01:12:33.620
[Guest]: or city managers, they tend to be a lot more sensible about like, what's needed, and they've

01:12:33.620 --> 01:12:40.940
[Guest]: been able to push through some interesting reforms as well. So yeah, I think it can happen

01:12:40.940 --> 01:12:46.660
[Guest]: at the bureaucratic level. But these are, I mean, this is again, I'm speaking from business

01:12:46.660 --> 01:12:53.780
[Guest]: as usual times, and this is like a completely different world that we're living in. So I

01:12:53.780 --> 01:12:59.500
[Guest]: don't know how their incentives and priorities have changed now. And what are the priorities

01:12:59.500 --> 01:13:04.940
[Guest]: of the government at the local level? Unfortunately, I mean, we have not, or at least I have not

01:13:04.940 --> 01:13:10.860
[Guest]: had a very deep look at it, or I mean, I've not been privy to that sort of those sort

01:13:10.860 --> 01:13:16.700
[Guest]: of conversations, because the goalposts change, the priorities change, you know, from one

01:13:16.700 --> 01:13:25.780
[Guest]: week to the next. So it will take, I think, some time for us to start talking about rebuilding

01:13:25.780 --> 01:13:29.740
[Guest]: reforms and, and all those kinds of things at the city level.

01:13:29.740 --> 01:13:32.940
[Amit Varma]: So in both your recent pieces on this, and the piece you wrote at the end of April in

01:13:32.940 --> 01:13:36.860
[Amit Varma]: first post, I think, and then the piece you wrote in July with Ruben and the Hindustan

01:13:36.860 --> 01:13:42.900
[Amit Varma]: Times, you'd laid out a bunch of things that the government could do to mitigate it. So

01:13:42.900 --> 01:13:48.180
[Amit Varma]: I'm going to go out, go to the four policy suggestions, which you and Ruben mentioned

01:13:48.180 --> 01:13:53.060
[Amit Varma]: in the July piece. And the first of these, we've already discussed where the first of

01:13:53.060 --> 01:13:57.620
[Amit Varma]: the policy responses you'd like is, quote, addressing crowding by increasing per capita

01:13:57.620 --> 01:14:03.780
[Amit Varma]: consumption of floor area by drastically reducing regulatory barriers to construction, stop

01:14:03.780 --> 01:14:08.340
[Amit Varma]: quote, which, you know, we've already discussed that, you know, FSI and other regulation which

01:14:08.340 --> 01:14:15.940
[Amit Varma]: prevents a far greater supply of housing can be relooked at. By the way, I wish you guys

01:14:15.940 --> 01:14:20.780
[Amit Varma]: use a little less jargon and simpler language for somebody like the Hindustan Times, but

01:14:20.780 --> 01:14:24.260
[Amit Varma]: never mind that these points are insightful and great. Let's let's turn to the second

01:14:24.260 --> 01:14:30.460
[Amit Varma]: of those where you say that quote, administratively, the crisis has taught us that a pandemic response

01:14:30.460 --> 01:14:35.700
[Amit Varma]: cannot be federally mandated and requires a decentralized, proximal and accountable

01:14:35.700 --> 01:14:41.340
[Amit Varma]: response to enable this city leaders need to be empowered to stop quote, and we've already

01:14:41.340 --> 01:14:45.140
[Amit Varma]: spoken a bit about how they are not empowered, there's a gap between power and accountability

01:14:45.140 --> 01:14:50.940
[Amit Varma]: and so on. But would you say that more than anything else, this pandemic really underscores

01:14:50.940 --> 01:14:55.820
[Amit Varma]: the importance of local self governance, because the conditions on the ground are so different

01:14:55.820 --> 01:15:01.020
[Amit Varma]: from neighborhood to neighborhood, that any central response, which looks at a one size

01:15:01.020 --> 01:15:08.820
[Amit Varma]: fits all sort of approach will necessarily fail. So one that do you think that this underscores

01:15:08.820 --> 01:15:14.280
[Amit Varma]: a need for greater local self governance? And do you think that there is state capacity

01:15:14.280 --> 01:15:18.260
[Amit Varma]: for such local self governance to actually work?

01:15:18.260 --> 01:15:25.660
[Guest]: So it is, of course, a story about empowering local self governance, but it's also a story

01:15:25.660 --> 01:15:32.780
[Guest]: of getting a polycentric governance system to work. So when I'm talking about a polycentric

01:15:32.780 --> 01:15:41.740
[Guest]: system, I'm talking about multiple tiers of government, and whose functions and responsibilities

01:15:41.740 --> 01:15:48.500
[Guest]: are demarcated, or basically the jurisdiction is demarcated in such a way that they can

01:15:48.500 --> 01:15:56.260
[Guest]: absorb any externalities. So and they're able to, you know, function at the right level

01:15:56.260 --> 01:16:02.820
[Guest]: of scale. So for instance, when we're talking about a, you know, an outbreak, there's multiple

01:16:02.820 --> 01:16:09.380
[Guest]: things going on, you need at the local level, you need empowerment, but you also need some

01:16:09.380 --> 01:16:15.820
[Guest]: higher level some thinking about, you know, the scale, I mean, the scale of thinking has

01:16:15.820 --> 01:16:21.100
[Guest]: to be slightly higher, where you are thinking about, you know, things like, what should

01:16:21.100 --> 01:16:27.100
[Guest]: be the testing strategies, and what should be the, the way in which you are deploying

01:16:27.100 --> 01:16:32.300
[Guest]: your resources. So state resources, because not all resources may be with the with the

01:16:32.300 --> 01:16:37.180
[Guest]: local body. And the reason why if, I mean, it makes sense to have them at the state,

01:16:37.180 --> 01:16:42.220
[Guest]: if the state is at the appropriate scale to be able to absorb the externalities that come

01:16:42.220 --> 01:16:48.220
[Guest]: up. So it's the fact that you need the polycentric system to work. So you need your local tire

01:16:48.220 --> 01:16:54.260
[Guest]: to work, you need your say, metropolitan tire, a level of government or metropolitan system

01:16:54.260 --> 01:16:59.140
[Guest]: to work, and you need your state system to work. And they're all doing different things.

01:16:59.140 --> 01:17:04.380
[Guest]: This polycentric governance actually was a term that was coined by Vincent and Eleanor

01:17:04.380 --> 01:17:11.700
[Guest]: Rostrom. And when they were looking at police, you know, the way police function in in the

01:17:11.700 --> 01:17:17.740
[Guest]: United States, and basically, why do you have sort of different tiers? And why should you

01:17:17.740 --> 01:17:22.740
[Guest]: either not, you know, it's a disaster, if you either consolidate everything, or you

01:17:22.740 --> 01:17:27.620
[Guest]: completely decentralize everything, because there are functions that you need different

01:17:27.620 --> 01:17:33.260
[Guest]: to to be assigned to different scales. So I know this was a bit of a digression, but

01:17:33.260 --> 01:17:39.540
[Guest]: I just wanted to highlight that we end up talking a lot about decentralization, because

01:17:39.540 --> 01:17:45.020
[Guest]: we know that that piece, I mean, at that level, things are completely broken, at least at

01:17:45.020 --> 01:17:51.340
[Guest]: the state level, some things work. But at this at the urban sort of city level, we are

01:17:51.340 --> 01:18:00.340
[Guest]: not giving cities enough revenues. The property tax collections are, like very, very minuscule.

01:18:00.340 --> 01:18:07.260
[Guest]: And cities like Mumbai earlier used to rely on octroi. And octroi went away because of

01:18:07.260 --> 01:18:14.060
[Guest]: the GST. So there's a massive shortfall, which has not been offset by any other revenue source.

01:18:14.060 --> 01:18:19.700
[Guest]: So there's a major following out of the revenues that cities have, if you don't have revenues,

01:18:19.700 --> 01:18:24.980
[Guest]: then then you don't have the power to undertake any sort of expenditures that can allow you

01:18:24.980 --> 01:18:30.660
[Guest]: to run at excess capacity, right? Because then everything is a is an exercise in saving

01:18:30.660 --> 01:18:36.740
[Guest]: budgets and saving expenditures. So that's the sort of problem that you have, when you

01:18:36.740 --> 01:18:41.980
[Guest]: don't have revenues at the city level. The second issue is, and I think this has been

01:18:41.980 --> 01:18:48.460
[Guest]: discussed earlier also, is you don't have leadership, you don't have accountable leadership,

01:18:48.460 --> 01:18:56.220
[Guest]: because the mayors don't have any real powers. And the municipal commissioners are sort of

01:18:56.220 --> 01:19:01.780
[Guest]: appointed by state governments, and they can their political masters at the state level.

01:19:01.780 --> 01:19:06.500
[Guest]: This is not to say that municipal commissioners have no incentive in ensuring the corporation's

01:19:06.500 --> 01:19:13.220
[Guest]: performed well. But it becomes too idiosyncratic, depending on the person that you have. And,

01:19:13.220 --> 01:19:17.780
[Guest]: you know, if you're lucky enough to have a great bureaucrat, then then it's good. But

01:19:17.780 --> 01:19:22.860
[Guest]: if he it's if he or she is bad, you can vote them out of power the next time, or take any

01:19:22.860 --> 01:19:28.340
[Guest]: action against them. If you had a system where the commissioner was accountable to the mayor,

01:19:28.340 --> 01:19:33.460
[Guest]: at least through the mayor, you could exercise some control over the actions of the commissioners,

01:19:33.460 --> 01:19:39.540
[Guest]: because the mayors are powerless. So that's basically your revenues are a mess, you don't

01:19:39.540 --> 01:19:46.060
[Guest]: have enough decentralized power. And the third thing that's missing is, you know, in terms

01:19:46.060 --> 01:19:50.860
[Guest]: of your functions and responsibilities that you have to undertake, there is a list which

01:19:50.860 --> 01:19:56.860
[Guest]: is called wealth taboo lists out the functions that an urban local body has to undertake.

01:19:56.860 --> 01:20:01.940
[Guest]: But the actual functions of the local body undertakes end up being far more. So whenever

01:20:01.940 --> 01:20:07.260
[Guest]: there is a centrally sponsored scheme, which the local bodies then have to undertake, those

01:20:07.260 --> 01:20:11.900
[Guest]: are additional unfunded mandates on the local body, which are a drain on the resources which

01:20:11.900 --> 01:20:18.180
[Guest]: are not coming on time, even things like your, your grants that the State Finance Commission

01:20:18.180 --> 01:20:23.540
[Guest]: has to give the local bodies, the untied grants don't always come through. So there's a whole

01:20:23.540 --> 01:20:32.100
[Guest]: bunch of these issues, which are I mean, lot more far experienced people have talked about

01:20:32.100 --> 01:20:38.180
[Guest]: it for far longer than even I've been a student or a researcher. So these things have been

01:20:38.180 --> 01:20:44.100
[Guest]: happening. I think since the 90s, even if even when we officially sort of recognize

01:20:44.100 --> 01:20:50.540
[Guest]: the thought tire at the level of government, in 92, and in 93, the problems have just sort

01:20:50.540 --> 01:20:55.900
[Guest]: of refused to go away. And there's a difference across states, some states to better some

01:20:55.900 --> 01:21:05.540
[Guest]: states to worse. But the, the these, I mean, if I have to look at what can be done, or

01:21:05.540 --> 01:21:12.220
[Guest]: what should be done in order to actually solve the problem, it seems like it, it needs to,

01:21:12.220 --> 01:21:18.460
[Guest]: I mean, there needs to be something that overrides the states, and maybe, and again, I hesitate

01:21:18.460 --> 01:21:23.260
[Guest]: to say this, because I know, like, even the central government is not the best way to

01:21:23.260 --> 01:21:28.740
[Guest]: sort of get around to doing things. But if the central government mandates certain things

01:21:28.740 --> 01:21:36.540
[Guest]: to, you know, in terms of the fixing the revenues and fixing the system of transferring grants,

01:21:36.540 --> 01:21:43.940
[Guest]: I think that would be a useful way to at least address the revenue situation within cities.

01:21:43.940 --> 01:21:50.060
[Guest]: Otherwise, you're finding many of them not receiving what they are due. And that's like

01:21:50.060 --> 01:21:55.020
[Guest]: millions of grants from the state finance commission, and from the center not being

01:21:55.020 --> 01:22:02.540
[Guest]: paid to them. So it's all a question of where the money is. And a question of and while

01:22:02.540 --> 01:22:08.820
[Guest]: the while the, the democratic representation and the, you know, the local empowerment and

01:22:08.820 --> 01:22:14.460
[Guest]: so on are key, I think the the revenue side of it is we don't hear about a lot in the

01:22:14.460 --> 01:22:20.540
[Guest]: public sphere, just maybe because it's sort of a dry topic to talk about, you know, like,

01:22:20.540 --> 01:22:27.980
[Guest]: it seems like, what is a grant in aid versus what is a tax and non tax revenue of a government

01:22:27.980 --> 01:22:33.500
[Guest]: is not the most exciting thing, I guess, a lay reader wants to look, look at and think

01:22:33.500 --> 01:22:38.700
[Guest]: that, but I think, I think that's a very, very critical issue in solving this problem.

01:22:38.700 --> 01:22:43.220
[Amit Varma]: I think some dry topics are enough to make the eyes wet. And it's a little sort of bizarre

01:22:43.220 --> 01:22:47.460
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, our Prime Minister was actually a chief minister for almost a decade and a

01:22:47.460 --> 01:22:51.780
[Amit Varma]: half before he came to power. So you'd imagine that he'd be cognizant and more concerned

01:22:51.780 --> 01:22:57.700
[Amit Varma]: about, you know, this aspect of it. And this is also incredibly tragic that I think we

01:22:57.700 --> 01:23:02.220
[Amit Varma]: have no option but to take a tangent for a moment or two to turn our mind away to something

01:23:02.220 --> 01:23:06.740
[Amit Varma]: else. So I'm not sure that that is less tragic. So while you were speaking of, you know, Bombay

01:23:06.740 --> 01:23:11.380
[Amit Varma]: situation with octroi that because of GST octroi revenues have completely gone because

01:23:11.380 --> 01:23:15.060
[Amit Varma]: the tax taxation system changed and there's nothing in its place, you know, a thought

01:23:15.060 --> 01:23:20.460
[Amit Varma]: that I've sometimes had came to mind. Now, the conventional view of the GST is that look,

01:23:20.460 --> 01:23:25.220
[Amit Varma]: it's, it's great in concept, because it takes away all the friction of all these multiple

01:23:25.220 --> 01:23:30.380
[Amit Varma]: taxes. And it was incredibly badly sort of implemented, which is why it turned out to

01:23:30.380 --> 01:23:34.900
[Amit Varma]: be such a disaster. In fact, I've received some valid criticism that I agree with that

01:23:34.900 --> 01:23:39.900
[Amit Varma]: in my episode with Arvind Subramaniam, I didn't push back hard enough on this, because there

01:23:39.900 --> 01:23:44.420
[Amit Varma]: is really nothing redeeming about the GST at all. But the other thought that I've had

01:23:44.420 --> 01:23:49.100
[Amit Varma]: is that even at a conceptual level, what kind of baffles me is that we keep saying local

01:23:49.100 --> 01:23:54.980
[Amit Varma]: self governance, local autonomy, and so on. But the GST is a centralizing, the GST comes

01:23:54.980 --> 01:23:59.060
[Amit Varma]: from a centralizing impulse, that what you should do is you should let different taxes

01:23:59.060 --> 01:24:03.020
[Amit Varma]: stack different states and different local authorities tax as they will, and then you

01:24:03.020 --> 01:24:08.020
[Amit Varma]: let the people decide and you let them kind of compete with each other. So it seems like

01:24:08.020 --> 01:24:12.260
[Amit Varma]: even at the level of concept, it's not that it's everything is good about it is that there

01:24:12.260 --> 01:24:16.740
[Amit Varma]: is this inherent trade off that you're moving to something centralizing and you're reducing

01:24:16.740 --> 01:24:22.100
[Amit Varma]: the autonomy of the states, which is something we actually see playing out, you know, as

01:24:22.100 --> 01:24:27.060
[Amit Varma]: we speak in terms of real term consequences. You have any thoughts on this?

01:24:27.060 --> 01:24:37.660
[Guest]: My sense is that so even if GST existed, and Octroi did not, a well functioning GST regime

01:24:37.660 --> 01:24:45.900
[Guest]: would have, I mean, I am not very anti the idea of GST. And I'm not saying that Octroi

01:24:45.900 --> 01:24:53.460
[Guest]: going away was like a complete like, unmitigated disaster. I'm just saying that this points

01:24:53.460 --> 01:25:00.340
[Guest]: to the lack of revenue sources that that corporations have and the one revenue source and this is

01:25:00.340 --> 01:25:06.020
[Guest]: justified in all types of theoretical frameworks as well. The one revenue source that all local

01:25:06.020 --> 01:25:13.820
[Guest]: bodies should have is property tax. And that's the revenue that they are supposed to really

01:25:13.820 --> 01:25:21.580
[Guest]: leverage and use. And that's something that we see governments not being able to do because

01:25:21.580 --> 01:25:28.500
[Guest]: there is not enough capacity to like, local body capacity to implement a robust property

01:25:28.500 --> 01:25:35.660
[Guest]: tax regime. We don't see our property tax systems being, you know, linked properly in

01:25:35.660 --> 01:25:42.300
[Guest]: terms of the underlying valuation of the property. We don't see them being buoyant. The rates,

01:25:42.300 --> 01:25:46.060
[Guest]: sometimes the rates are too low, even if the rates are not low enough, like people are

01:25:46.060 --> 01:25:51.860
[Guest]: simply not paying and you don't have any way of tracking those who do and making them pay.

01:25:51.860 --> 01:25:56.940
[Guest]: So my sense is that there's still there's so much work to do in terms of improving our

01:25:56.940 --> 01:26:04.180
[Guest]: property tax system alone. Getting that right would be, you know, a major win for urban

01:26:04.180 --> 01:26:12.420
[Guest]: local bodies. And the other set of sources that cities have, and this is, I mean, not

01:26:12.420 --> 01:26:17.780
[Guest]: perhaps it's not correct to say that cities have it because land is a state subject, but

01:26:17.780 --> 01:26:25.220
[Guest]: cities also have, you know, very, very high valued land being used very inefficiently.

01:26:25.220 --> 01:26:30.980
[Guest]: And there is government property that is being, or government land that is like vacant. And

01:26:30.980 --> 01:26:40.180
[Guest]: these sort of properties and inefficiently used land are a major, can be leveraged to

01:26:40.180 --> 01:26:44.900
[Guest]: raise a lot of money for cities. Especially if you, you know, walk around in Mumbai and

01:26:44.900 --> 01:26:51.020
[Guest]: see an empty plot of land, you know, how expensive that could be. And just because your government,

01:26:51.020 --> 01:26:55.580
[Guest]: you're saying you don't have any incentive to use it or to lease it out to, you know,

01:26:55.580 --> 01:27:01.700
[Guest]: the highest bidder and so on. My hope was that with Octroi being taken away, there would

01:27:01.700 --> 01:27:09.900
[Guest]: be a lot more dynamism being shown and using these land-based revenue sources more intelligently.

01:27:09.900 --> 01:27:15.460
[Guest]: But that again, has not happened at as much of an extent as I would have hoped. So the

01:27:15.460 --> 01:27:21.660
[Guest]: property tax and the land-based revenue systems together would have at least, you know, get

01:27:21.660 --> 01:27:28.060
[Guest]: help. Cities have a very decent base of revenues and that would have then, you know, allowed

01:27:28.060 --> 01:27:34.620
[Guest]: them to do other like more sophisticated things like municipal bonds and, you know, raise

01:27:34.620 --> 01:27:41.380
[Guest]: money from the market to finance infrastructure and so on. But yeah, that's, that's not happened.

01:27:41.380 --> 01:27:47.900
[Guest]: Again, I mean, I won't be able to articulate why it's not happened, but it certainly hasn't

01:27:47.900 --> 01:27:48.900
[Guest]: happened.

01:27:48.900 --> 01:27:52.260
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. In fact, I had an episode with Rajesh Jain, which we'll also link from the show

01:27:52.260 --> 01:27:58.020
[Amit Varma]: notes and you must be familiar with sort of his grand campaign of, you know, he estimated

01:27:58.020 --> 01:28:02.580
[Amit Varma]: how much land the state holds across the country, including in Mumbai. And these are not trivial

01:28:02.580 --> 01:28:06.660
[Amit Varma]: amounts of land. These are such huge amounts of land that if you actually figure out ways

01:28:06.660 --> 01:28:11.620
[Amit Varma]: to monetize them properly, according to Rajesh, you could actually afford to give a UBI to

01:28:11.620 --> 01:28:16.160
[Amit Varma]: the whole country just from that alone. So we'll link that episode from the show notes

01:28:16.160 --> 01:28:21.700
[Amit Varma]: and leave it to listeners to judge for themselves. You know, having spoken about the state, it's

01:28:21.700 --> 01:28:25.620
[Amit Varma]: time now to get back to the more cheerful subject of the pandemic, which actually takes

01:28:25.620 --> 01:28:30.400
[Amit Varma]: us back to the state because a third of the things that you and Ruben suggested were quote,

01:28:30.400 --> 01:28:34.300
[Amit Varma]: Rural protection systems need to be redesigned to protect the poor and vulnerable in urban

01:28:34.300 --> 01:28:42.060
[Amit Varma]: areas, comma, in addition to the current focus on rural settlements, stop quote. Now, whatever

01:28:42.060 --> 01:28:47.740
[Amit Varma]: I'm familiar with happening in sort of urban areas has actually happened because of private

01:28:47.740 --> 01:28:53.660
[Amit Varma]: initiative, like people give a bad rap to markets and so on. But everything that has

01:28:53.660 --> 01:28:58.140
[Amit Varma]: been done for the suffering here is through voluntary action. I think my friend Ruben

01:28:58.140 --> 01:29:04.660
[Amit Varma]: Mascarenas and you know, his friends fed 10s of 1000s if not 100s of 1000s of people during

01:29:04.660 --> 01:29:11.660
[Amit Varma]: that difficult period of COVID and one could see the government doing absolutely nothing,

01:29:11.660 --> 01:29:17.920
[Amit Varma]: at least relatively so. So tell me a bit about what you mean by social protection systems

01:29:17.920 --> 01:29:24.120
[Amit Varma]: for urban areas? What would it entail? You know, what are the incentives against just

01:29:24.120 --> 01:29:31.500
[Guest]: implementing those and and so on? So social protection systems would fall into a bunch

01:29:31.500 --> 01:29:37.500
[Guest]: of different categories. So there will be things like livelihood protection. There's

01:29:37.500 --> 01:29:42.980
[Guest]: things like livelihood support, where you provide income support, there's access to

01:29:42.980 --> 01:29:50.460
[Guest]: so your public distribution system, which is your ration, shops and so on. They form

01:29:50.460 --> 01:29:59.220
[Guest]: a part of the social protection systems. You also have schemes targeted to certain types

01:29:59.220 --> 01:30:05.900
[Guest]: of population, like the elderly, the ones or women, and so on. So all of these are your

01:30:05.900 --> 01:30:13.740
[Guest]: sort of, you know, all the schemes under which a poor person or a poor household can avail

01:30:13.740 --> 01:30:19.380
[Guest]: some benefits or the other for different reasons. So their food needs can food security needs

01:30:19.380 --> 01:30:25.380
[Guest]: are taken care of through PDF. And then, you know, livelihood needs, maybe they are not

01:30:25.380 --> 01:30:30.360
[Guest]: livelihood needs, but some kind of income support may be provided through these pensions,

01:30:30.360 --> 01:30:36.540
[Guest]: social pensions that the government provides. And if you have a potential livelihood shock,

01:30:36.540 --> 01:30:41.760
[Guest]: in terms of unemployment, you have your employment guarantee schemes that work. Now, all of them

01:30:41.760 --> 01:30:47.900
[Guest]: are designed for a rural population and a rural country. As I mentioned earlier, right,

01:30:47.900 --> 01:30:54.580
[Guest]: your your NREGA is is a rural scheme. So if you're an urban household facing a temporary

01:30:54.580 --> 01:31:00.100
[Guest]: employment shock, there's no employment guarantee scheme for you. PDS, because it's linked to

01:31:00.100 --> 01:31:07.180
[Guest]: and again, to be fair, there's a lot of now a lot of churn and a lot of rethinking of

01:31:07.180 --> 01:31:12.260
[Guest]: these systems. PDS, again, is linked to the ration card, which is the place you stay.

01:31:12.260 --> 01:31:18.060
[Guest]: So if you're a migrant, you cannot avail PDS. Because if your address is somewhere outside

01:31:18.060 --> 01:31:23.580
[Guest]: of the state, you cannot go to a ration shop and ask for ration. So there's just all these

01:31:23.580 --> 01:31:32.300
[Guest]: barriers to, you know, and, again, the barriers may have come out of just the way the architecture

01:31:32.300 --> 01:31:38.100
[Guest]: of the system is where you have, because the states are responsible for providing most

01:31:38.100 --> 01:31:43.660
[Guest]: of and implementing most of the social protection schemes. They just end up sort of being very,

01:31:43.660 --> 01:31:50.020
[Guest]: very different across and you end up then asking for a proof all the time of, you know,

01:31:50.020 --> 01:31:58.020
[Guest]: you belonging to the state to be able to avail these benefits. So these kinds of issues have

01:31:58.020 --> 01:32:04.620
[Guest]: in the pandemic time really, really hurt the poor. And there is an opportunity here to

01:32:04.620 --> 01:32:11.740
[Guest]: think more creatively. Again, given you now have some technology, you have your, you know,

01:32:11.740 --> 01:32:17.460
[Guest]: Jan Dhan accounts, and you have some sort of a mobile technology in which you're able

01:32:17.460 --> 01:32:25.260
[Guest]: to reach people. There is a way to try and be link, say, PDS from where the person originally

01:32:25.260 --> 01:32:33.020
[Guest]: lives in. There's a way to try and think about an urban employment guarantee scheme. There's

01:32:33.020 --> 01:32:41.220
[Guest]: a way to try and think about housing for migrant workers in terms of currently I mean, of course,

01:32:41.220 --> 01:32:46.700
[Guest]: most of them live in cheap rental accommodation in slums and so on. But there's also such

01:32:46.700 --> 01:32:54.460
[Guest]: a massive gap in what we know, like collecting information about, you know, how do migrant

01:32:54.460 --> 01:33:00.700
[Guest]: workers actually go about surviving in the city? Like, how do they even access anything

01:33:00.700 --> 01:33:09.180
[Guest]: from like a bag to a ration to, you know, housing, creating that database of knowledge,

01:33:09.180 --> 01:33:13.620
[Guest]: in order to inform your policy design, that's important. That's an activity that needs to

01:33:13.620 --> 01:33:18.420
[Guest]: be taken up again, not necessarily always by the government, it could be philanthropy

01:33:18.420 --> 01:33:24.340
[Guest]: organizations, it could be NGOs, it could be a partnership, a consortium of these different

01:33:24.340 --> 01:33:30.780
[Guest]: organizations coming together to do this. But that I mean, building that knowledge base

01:33:30.780 --> 01:33:37.060
[Guest]: is also equally important. So, I would think that A, the knowledge creation and collecting

01:33:37.060 --> 01:33:42.900
[Guest]: information and B, redesigning or thinking about redesigning your employment schemes,

01:33:42.900 --> 01:33:49.420
[Guest]: your PDS schemes, and even your other say, social pension schemes, in order to actually

01:33:49.420 --> 01:33:56.580
[Guest]: benefit the, you know, the most vulnerable people and reach them is critical. And I think

01:33:56.580 --> 01:34:03.380
[Guest]: that those conversations are happening. And I'm a little more optimistic about that end

01:34:03.380 --> 01:34:10.260
[Guest]: of things that I think things may, I mean, we may end up making some interesting policy

01:34:10.260 --> 01:34:15.860
[Guest]: reforms that hopefully will have much needed and long lasting impact.

01:34:15.860 --> 01:34:19.420
[Amit Varma]: So I have two questions here. And I'll ask them separately, because one feedback I've

01:34:19.420 --> 01:34:24.420
[Amit Varma]: also got is when I ask a two part question, guests get confused and answer only the second

01:34:24.420 --> 01:34:28.980
[Amit Varma]: part because my questions go on for so long. So I'm going to ask these parts separately.

01:34:28.980 --> 01:34:35.220
[Amit Varma]: And part one is that it strikes me that in all of this, there are inherent issues with

01:34:35.220 --> 01:34:40.740
[Amit Varma]: how difficult these are to implement. For example, there's just a question of identifying

01:34:40.740 --> 01:34:44.460
[Amit Varma]: who should be a recipient or whatever, you know, if you say that, okay, we are going

01:34:44.460 --> 01:34:48.780
[Amit Varma]: to give some cover for sudden unemployment because of pandemic. But when so much of your

01:34:48.780 --> 01:34:53.940
[Amit Varma]: economy is an informal sector, how do you even identify and classify unemployment when

01:34:53.940 --> 01:34:58.620
[Amit Varma]: you haven't recognized the employment to begin with? And you know, there are so many leakage

01:34:58.620 --> 01:35:07.020
[Amit Varma]: is within the system. So the question here is that, given all of these, assuming that

01:35:07.020 --> 01:35:11.140
[Amit Varma]: you get the government and power to agree with you that these are the things that need

01:35:11.140 --> 01:35:18.260
[Amit Varma]: to be done on a scale of one to 10, how likely is it that state capacity will actually be

01:35:18.260 --> 01:35:21.580
[Amit Varma]: up to the task of implementing these?

01:35:21.580 --> 01:35:25.820
[Guest]: That's I don't know how to how to sort of...

01:35:25.820 --> 01:35:29.260
[Amit Varma]: I just realized I might have put you on a spot because if people in government are listening

01:35:29.260 --> 01:35:30.260
[Amit Varma]: to this, they'll be like...

01:35:30.260 --> 01:35:35.860
[Guest]: I mean, that's not the issue at all. I'm just trying to think about how does one quantify

01:35:35.860 --> 01:35:40.260
[Guest]: these kinds of things at the end of the day isn't any scale like an arbitrary thing. But

01:35:40.260 --> 01:35:49.020
[Guest]: from a qualitative perspective of like really badly equipped to like they'll do a great

01:35:49.020 --> 01:35:58.940
[Guest]: job of implementing it. It will depend on what we end up designing. And again, I may

01:35:58.940 --> 01:36:08.220
[Guest]: be a little more hopeful because just because there seems to be enough A, like smart people

01:36:08.220 --> 01:36:17.260
[Guest]: working on this problem and people who had very, very deep experience looking and engaging

01:36:17.260 --> 01:36:22.620
[Guest]: with state governments who are sort of thinking through these problems, not like some fly

01:36:22.620 --> 01:36:31.660
[Guest]: by night operators being brought in to solve the problem. If it is designed well, and if

01:36:31.660 --> 01:36:39.460
[Guest]: you're using the technology that you have responsibly and in order to actually benefit

01:36:39.460 --> 01:36:45.580
[Guest]: the people in terms of ensuring that you're identifying them while all the protection

01:36:45.580 --> 01:36:52.820
[Guest]: mechanisms are in place. I think I'm more optimistic about this. I feel that we would

01:36:52.820 --> 01:37:02.260
[Guest]: be able to do something. So I would say maybe in seven out of 10. I did end up giving a

01:37:02.260 --> 01:37:03.260
[Amit Varma]: number.

01:37:03.260 --> 01:37:07.300
[Amit Varma]: No, I think it's, you know, even if no one is going to hold you to a number, obviously,

01:37:07.300 --> 01:37:13.500
[Amit Varma]: because social science is so inexact in these ways. But I find just asking people about,

01:37:13.500 --> 01:37:17.980
[Amit Varma]: you know, on the scale forces them to sort of think a little harder about it. And the

01:37:17.980 --> 01:37:22.700
[Amit Varma]: exercise of coming up with a number is fun. My instinct would be actually I mean, it's

01:37:22.700 --> 01:37:26.500
[Amit Varma]: the question is phrased wrongly. I mean, what are the chances that whatever your design

01:37:26.500 --> 01:37:30.700
[Amit Varma]: gets implemented, I would say it's obviously zero because they can't implement it all.

01:37:30.700 --> 01:37:37.020
[Amit Varma]: But how much of it is likely to get implemented on a scale of zero to 10? I don't know. I

01:37:37.020 --> 01:37:41.500
[Amit Varma]: mean, seven seems to me to be on the high side of the of my range. But if I had to give

01:37:41.500 --> 01:37:47.060
[Amit Varma]: it a range, yeah, maybe like two to seven, which is a way.

01:37:47.060 --> 01:37:55.860
[Guest]: I think I would rather be a little more generous. And then I, you know, of course, can correct

01:37:55.860 --> 01:38:00.580
[Guest]: myself later. And we can have a follow up conversation. You can ask me again.

01:38:00.580 --> 01:38:05.340
[Amit Varma]: No, I mean, you know, I prefer your approach, because the point is that if you thought it

01:38:05.340 --> 01:38:09.980
[Amit Varma]: was less than seven, you might think that it is not worthwhile my doing any work here.

01:38:09.980 --> 01:38:13.220
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, I would be perfectly happy if you thought it was 10. I would not argue

01:38:13.220 --> 01:38:17.140
[Amit Varma]: with you there. Because, you know, we need people like you more than we need people like

01:38:17.140 --> 01:38:25.780
[Amit Varma]: me to make change sort of happen. My second question is this, that it's obvious that there,

01:38:25.780 --> 01:38:30.260
[Amit Varma]: you know, needs to be disaster mitigation, that, you know, when a crisis strikes, you

01:38:30.260 --> 01:38:36.140
[Amit Varma]: need to find ways to give relief to the people whatever form that takes. Now, there are sort

01:38:36.140 --> 01:38:40.420
[Amit Varma]: of two philosophical questions that come up there. Somebody could easily pop up and say

01:38:40.420 --> 01:38:44.620
[Amit Varma]: that, boss, I lost my job because of COVID. So you're giving me compensation. But if I

01:38:44.620 --> 01:38:50.020
[Amit Varma]: lose my job at any other time, for any other reason, like say demonetization, which was

01:38:50.020 --> 01:38:56.020
[Amit Varma]: not a natural disaster, but a manmade disaster, then why am I not due compensation? Why are

01:38:56.020 --> 01:39:00.420
[Amit Varma]: you recognizing one kind of suffering than another, which becomes a philosophical question.

01:39:00.420 --> 01:39:06.440
[Amit Varma]: And the other issue that then comes up is about the dangers of potentially building

01:39:06.440 --> 01:39:11.820
[Amit Varma]: patronage systems, which then never get dismantled. And therefore, that sort of becomes a trap

01:39:11.820 --> 01:39:16.580
[Amit Varma]: because the moment you build any kind of entitlement into the system, look, the political economy

01:39:16.580 --> 01:39:22.420
[Amit Varma]: is such that it's simply never going to go away. And while it is good at that short term

01:39:22.420 --> 01:39:26.580
[Amit Varma]: moment, again, the pandemic paradox that there is a disaster and people can't eat, so you

01:39:26.580 --> 01:39:30.980
[Amit Varma]: obviously have to do something about it. But if you set it in stone, then the opportunity

01:39:30.980 --> 01:39:37.260
[Amit Varma]: cost of that is a long term reforms and the building the long term structures that would

01:39:37.260 --> 01:39:42.340
[Amit Varma]: help the whole nation right to prosperity in the long run so that these mitigating measures

01:39:42.340 --> 01:39:48.100
[Amit Varma]: are not needed at all or not needed the next time. So how does one sort of deal with this?

01:39:48.100 --> 01:39:52.100
[Amit Varma]: Because one thing that does seem to be happening, you know, is that during pandemics like this

01:39:52.100 --> 01:39:57.180
[Amit Varma]: or during times of crisis, the state just expands, and then it doesn't contract back

01:39:57.180 --> 01:40:02.700
[Amit Varma]: to where it was. And a lot of this expansion is not necessarily expansion in the good sense

01:40:02.700 --> 01:40:06.420
[Amit Varma]: that we would want that it's doing the duties that it should and getting stronger in that

01:40:06.420 --> 01:40:12.700
[Amit Varma]: regard, but is sort of all these other things. So what are your thoughts on this? Is this

01:40:12.700 --> 01:40:15.580
[Amit Varma]: a danger that you kind of grapple with?

01:40:15.580 --> 01:40:22.140
[Guest]: So about the question of, okay, why are we offering SOPs in one case? And why not the

01:40:22.140 --> 01:40:29.700
[Guest]: other? Why a national disaster? Why not a man-made disaster? The point is that you have

01:40:29.700 --> 01:40:36.620
[Guest]: a large section of population that has been completely devastated, right? And there's

01:40:36.620 --> 01:40:46.260
[Guest]: so many, so many, so many examples and stories and news articles and so on. I mean, what

01:40:46.260 --> 01:40:54.500
[Guest]: is, I mean, I'm sorry if I'm being a bit wishy-washy, but what is the morally right thing to do

01:40:54.500 --> 01:41:01.940
[Guest]: for the government or for the state? And if the state should not, ought not to do this,

01:41:01.940 --> 01:41:09.940
[Guest]: then you know, which is protect its most vulnerable citizens or try and in whatever way, given

01:41:09.940 --> 01:41:18.780
[Guest]: whatever implementation constraints and so on, should it not attempt to alleviate some

01:41:18.780 --> 01:41:26.100
[Guest]: of these problems and some of these shocks that people have had. And where I come on

01:41:26.100 --> 01:41:32.820
[Guest]: the side is that the state must do something about it. To your second point about whether

01:41:32.820 --> 01:41:39.580
[Guest]: or not it ends up being just something that will never go away and just an entitlement

01:41:39.580 --> 01:41:46.940
[Guest]: and so on. If we take the case of what the developed countries are doing, they're also

01:41:46.940 --> 01:41:53.980
[Guest]: offering these COVID-related measures and so on. We are also offering the COVID-related

01:41:53.980 --> 01:42:01.820
[Guest]: schemes. We are also at the same time trying to build a system or rebuild a social protection

01:42:01.820 --> 01:42:10.300
[Guest]: architecture from some sort of different principles, right? So where earlier you were just like,

01:42:10.300 --> 01:42:15.980
[Guest]: you know, saying, okay, whoever, let's focus on rural areas and let's, it's incumbent on

01:42:15.980 --> 01:42:21.060
[Guest]: the citizen to be able to fulfill 50 criteria to be able to get this. Now we're like, let's

01:42:21.060 --> 01:42:27.900
[Guest]: tolerate some inclusion errors. It's okay if people who don't need to get it end up

01:42:27.900 --> 01:42:34.220
[Guest]: getting it. A, the reason is that you're, I don't think that it, so here's the thing.

01:42:34.220 --> 01:42:40.340
[Guest]: So if you provide a system where you are giving a larger number of people, you're expanding

01:42:40.340 --> 01:42:48.260
[Guest]: the net and then, you know, whoever gets in, gets in. If you have some self-selecting mechanisms,

01:42:48.260 --> 01:42:52.500
[Guest]: you may find people opting out because I mean, frankly, what will I do with a pension of

01:42:52.500 --> 01:42:58.500
[Guest]: 500 rupees per month, I mean, per month for the rest of my life. And if I, you know, if

01:42:58.500 --> 01:43:04.020
[Guest]: I don't need it, I can, I'm happy to give it away. The point is that if you expand the

01:43:04.020 --> 01:43:11.340
[Guest]: net enough, you may have some inclusion errors, but it's fine because it's better to do that

01:43:11.340 --> 01:43:18.100
[Guest]: rather than to exclude the people who actually need it. And that is a, that is a bigger problem.

01:43:18.100 --> 01:43:23.780
[Guest]: And as you sort of, I don't know if there's been any rigorous study that looks at whether

01:43:23.780 --> 01:43:31.700
[Guest]: or not, if once you have a social protection scheme, do people end up, you know, using

01:43:31.700 --> 01:43:39.340
[Guest]: that as a crutch and, and therefore not end up striving to aspire to improve their livelihoods.

01:43:39.340 --> 01:43:44.700
[Guest]: I don't see this as a very, it's, you know, mutually exclusive thing that if you have

01:43:44.700 --> 01:43:50.340
[Guest]: this, then I have no incentives, perhaps the safety nets are so low that you would, you're

01:43:50.340 --> 01:43:55.580
[Guest]: much better off in the long run, if you want, if you try and get out of this dependency

01:43:55.580 --> 01:44:02.460
[Guest]: on the social safety systems or the social protection schemes. So if that ends up happening,

01:44:02.460 --> 01:44:08.300
[Guest]: and I'm more optimistic in the sense that I do feel people want to see their lives get

01:44:08.300 --> 01:44:12.300
[Guest]: better and their children's life getting better. And they know that if relying on those is

01:44:12.300 --> 01:44:19.100
[Guest]: not the way that's going to happen, they will also want to strive to, you know, get higher

01:44:19.100 --> 01:44:23.820
[Guest]: incomes and move out of this. And so you will end up, you may still have the architecture

01:44:23.820 --> 01:44:29.300
[Guest]: in place, you may have more people coming in as, as other people move out of it. In

01:44:29.300 --> 01:44:33.900
[Guest]: that sense, it will remain entrenched. But I don't think that, you know, for the same

01:44:33.900 --> 01:44:40.580
[Guest]: set of beneficiaries, they end up being dependent on it for all their lives. I think it's more

01:44:40.580 --> 01:44:43.820
[Guest]: of people move out, and then more people come in.

01:44:43.820 --> 01:44:47.260
[Amit Varma]: So let me let me sort of, as I was thinking aloud, let me continue thinking aloud and

01:44:47.260 --> 01:44:52.540
[Amit Varma]: kind of clarify what I meant. What I meant was not that patronage is necessarily a bad

01:44:52.540 --> 01:44:57.860
[Amit Varma]: thing in all contexts. In fact, on the contrary, I agree with you that it is our moral responsibility

01:44:57.860 --> 01:45:04.180
[Amit Varma]: to alleviate the sort of pain and the suffering that is out there. But I would add to that

01:45:04.180 --> 01:45:09.180
[Amit Varma]: and say that much as we think of COVID-19 as a disaster, it's also a fact that we are

01:45:09.180 --> 01:45:13.700
[Amit Varma]: in the middle of an ongoing disaster, which has lasted 73 years and is caused by the Indian

01:45:13.700 --> 01:45:17.340
[Amit Varma]: state. I wrote a column about this, which I linked from the show notes. But look, here's

01:45:17.340 --> 01:45:22.860
[Amit Varma]: the thing. Every day 3000 children die in India of starvation. That's almost 100,000

01:45:22.860 --> 01:45:27.340
[Amit Varma]: kids in India dying of starvation every month. Right? And to me, that's a disaster. And we

01:45:27.340 --> 01:45:31.260
[Amit Varma]: need to do something about that. But it's normalized. And of course, those deaths are

01:45:31.260 --> 01:45:35.860
[Amit Varma]: dispersed and those deaths are invisible to us because they're probably happening in areas

01:45:35.860 --> 01:45:43.980
[Amit Varma]: where the media doesn't go and cover all of that. So we can ignore that. And so my broader

01:45:43.980 --> 01:45:49.020
[Amit Varma]: point of what the state should do about what is happening, for example, if 3000 kids are

01:45:49.020 --> 01:45:52.380
[Amit Varma]: dying every day of starvation, what do you do about that? And my broader point is that

01:45:52.380 --> 01:45:57.700
[Amit Varma]: you need a two prong strategy, which I think most people would agree with, which is that

01:45:57.700 --> 01:46:02.380
[Amit Varma]: in the short term, you feed them, you figure out a way to get food to them, get money to

01:46:02.380 --> 01:46:05.900
[Amit Varma]: them, and you sort out the problem with short term patronage. And you have to do that. It's

01:46:05.900 --> 01:46:10.500
[Amit Varma]: your moral responsibility to do that. But at the same time, you put in place long term

01:46:10.500 --> 01:46:15.140
[Amit Varma]: structures by which they can at some point in time feed themselves. And therefore, you

01:46:15.140 --> 01:46:19.100
[Amit Varma]: don't need to, for example, to use your the example of the figure that you named, you

01:46:19.100 --> 01:46:23.340
[Amit Varma]: don't need to give 500 bucks a month to anybody after a period of time, because everybody

01:46:23.340 --> 01:46:26.700
[Amit Varma]: is earning so much more that they don't really care for that. That's your long term goal.

01:46:26.700 --> 01:46:30.940
[Amit Varma]: I think what often happens in India is that we look for the short term fixes. And then

01:46:30.940 --> 01:46:35.020
[Amit Varma]: we'll say ki hume jo karna tha humne kar diya and now we don't need to do anything else.

01:46:35.020 --> 01:46:40.620
[Amit Varma]: For example, when it comes to something like the agricultural crisis, we see this, where

01:46:40.620 --> 01:46:45.380
[Amit Varma]: now it's almost become a fait accompli that everyone has to promise farm loan waivers,

01:46:45.380 --> 01:46:50.140
[Amit Varma]: which is often a necessary anaesthetic in a short term sense, but you never end up making

01:46:50.140 --> 01:46:56.180
[Amit Varma]: the long term reforms that you actually need to, to solve the problem. Because one, those

01:46:56.180 --> 01:47:00.460
[Amit Varma]: incentives aren't there, those solutions are not in demand, because they're unintuitive

01:47:00.460 --> 01:47:05.180
[Amit Varma]: very often for most people, a politician's time horizon extends to the next election.

01:47:05.180 --> 01:47:10.540
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, some reforms could take 1015 years to play out. So yeah, I'm not disputing

01:47:10.540 --> 01:47:14.820
[Amit Varma]: anything you're saying. And I'm just kind of clarifying where I was coming from. There's

01:47:14.820 --> 01:47:20.740
[Amit Varma]: no question at the end of this. But I'll, I'll, since we are talking about the state,

01:47:20.740 --> 01:47:27.360
[Amit Varma]: I will get to a question that I did have, which is the writer jack shanker and a piece

01:47:27.360 --> 01:47:32.020
[Amit Varma]: in the Guardian, you know, wrote a piece on cities post COVID, where I found this paragraph

01:47:32.020 --> 01:47:36.640
[Amit Varma]: quite fascinating, very right score. South Korea, one of the countries worst affected

01:47:36.640 --> 01:47:41.180
[Amit Varma]: by the disease has also posted some of the lowest mortality rates and achievement that

01:47:41.180 --> 01:47:46.700
[Amit Varma]: can be traced in part to a series of technological innovations, including controversially, the

01:47:46.700 --> 01:47:54.420
[Amit Varma]: mapping and publication of infected patients movement. And, you know, so this kind of strikes

01:47:54.420 --> 01:48:01.900
[Amit Varma]: me as another, an interesting example, of course, of the trade off between security

01:48:01.900 --> 01:48:07.580
[Amit Varma]: and privacy, in this case, security against the virus. But also, then a pandemic like

01:48:07.580 --> 01:48:13.340
[Amit Varma]: this can become an excuse for a for creeping authoritarianism, where, you know, and you

01:48:13.340 --> 01:48:18.340
[Amit Varma]: yourself have referred earlier in this podcast to surveillance in positive terms, that it's

01:48:18.340 --> 01:48:22.820
[Amit Varma]: something that helps you control the disease. So how are we to what are we to make this

01:48:22.820 --> 01:48:28.980
[Amit Varma]: trade off, especially when we live in times that there are worries about such authoritarianism

01:48:28.980 --> 01:48:35.260
[Amit Varma]: and about the state getting too much power over the lives of people? So how does one

01:48:35.260 --> 01:48:40.020
[Amit Varma]: think about this at a conceptual level? And then at a political economy level? How does

01:48:40.020 --> 01:48:46.180
[Amit Varma]: one sort of negotiate this because the impulse of the state will always be to, you know,

01:48:46.180 --> 01:48:53.100
[Guest]: get as much control as they can? So it's great you asked that, because that's my real worry.

01:48:53.100 --> 01:48:57.420
[Guest]: It's not so much the fact that if you have a patronage system in place, it just won't

01:48:57.420 --> 01:49:02.900
[Guest]: go away. My worry is that if you have a surveillance system in place, it will just try and, you

01:49:02.900 --> 01:49:12.580
[Guest]: know, dig its claws deeper and just not go away. And that's a very, very real fear, even

01:49:12.580 --> 01:49:18.940
[Guest]: in a democratic society, like India, because we still have so many draconian laws from

01:49:18.940 --> 01:49:25.020
[Guest]: the colonial times that have, you know, continued and that have been used time and again by

01:49:25.020 --> 01:49:34.460
[Guest]: the state as a means to, to thwart dissent, to get people to stop criticizing or stop

01:49:34.460 --> 01:49:42.060
[Guest]: being critical and of your private information through say, mobile phone apps and the like

01:49:42.060 --> 01:49:51.380
[Guest]: being collected by the state is extremely worrying. And I'm not a privacy expert or

01:49:51.380 --> 01:49:57.380
[Guest]: a data governance expert. So in terms of thinking through solutions, I will not know how we

01:49:57.380 --> 01:50:03.820
[Guest]: can think of safeguarding people's privacy, like what steps should people take? My other

01:50:03.820 --> 01:50:11.500
[Guest]: concern is also that we don't have enough political leaders who can stand up or like

01:50:11.500 --> 01:50:16.780
[Guest]: talk about this as an issue and actually be an effective that sort of checks and balance

01:50:16.780 --> 01:50:22.980
[Guest]: in the legislature is, is not no longer there. And so, I mean, I'm very, very concerned and

01:50:22.980 --> 01:50:29.380
[Guest]: very, very pessimistic about this about and very cynical about the fact that you are developing

01:50:29.380 --> 01:50:35.780
[Guest]: systems in which you are giving more and more power to the state, and it's going to end

01:50:35.780 --> 01:50:45.780
[Guest]: up having some unhealthy consequences in terms of what can be done to assure this. I mean,

01:50:45.780 --> 01:50:50.300
[Guest]: to mitigate this or whether or not there was another way to go about doing this without

01:50:50.300 --> 01:50:55.100
[Guest]: giving the state so much power, what would the other alternatives that we could have

01:50:55.100 --> 01:51:04.340
[Guest]: taken up? I'm not sure that I have the answers to that question either. But it is, if you

01:51:04.340 --> 01:51:10.460
[Guest]: look at what other state, I mean, not South Korea, but say, if you look at what Europe

01:51:10.460 --> 01:51:17.300
[Guest]: does, and the Europeans are massively concerned about privacy, right, and individual right

01:51:17.300 --> 01:51:26.020
[Guest]: to privacy and so on. Perhaps there are models there that could have been used. But I think

01:51:26.020 --> 01:51:31.780
[Guest]: that that ship has sailed. I mean, we've already ended up doing a lot of things that were unnecessary,

01:51:31.780 --> 01:51:40.300
[Guest]: that were intrusive. So, yeah, I mean, I don't know if I mean, that is all the supposedly

01:51:40.300 --> 01:51:46.700
[Guest]: the courts that that need that will protect the individual from any kind of state overreach.

01:51:46.700 --> 01:51:52.580
[Guest]: But I mean, I think, I think I'm not very optimistic about that, as well. So yeah, it's

01:51:52.580 --> 01:51:57.660
[Amit Varma]: all bad news. I'm glad you said supposedly when you said it supposedly the courts that

01:51:57.660 --> 01:52:04.540
[Amit Varma]: will protect us know we are recording this on September 9. And, you know, the way the

01:52:04.540 --> 01:52:09.660
[Amit Varma]: media hounded Rhea Chakravorty, and she eventually got arrested for drugs possession and cannabis

01:52:09.660 --> 01:52:15.220
[Amit Varma]: shouldn't even be illegal, but she got arrested for that, even though no actual drugs were

01:52:15.220 --> 01:52:19.060
[Amit Varma]: recovered from her. It was I think, on the basis of WhatsApp messages or something where

01:52:19.060 --> 01:52:25.860
[Amit Varma]: she was, you know, getting something for Sushant Singh Rajput to smoke. So it's kind of ridiculous.

01:52:25.860 --> 01:52:32.020
[Amit Varma]: I'm also reminded of how, you know, the government released the tea star settle words credit

01:52:32.020 --> 01:52:36.380
[Amit Varma]: card record wants to show that she brought alcohol from a store. I mean, what freaking

01:52:36.380 --> 01:52:42.700
[Amit Varma]: business is that of anyone? So the thing here is, even if we had a proper laws protecting

01:52:42.700 --> 01:52:47.540
[Amit Varma]: us the way the state is, and how, you know, it's also dysfunctional, it probably won't

01:52:47.540 --> 01:52:53.180
[Amit Varma]: even matter. Let's let's kind of go back to the fourth of the suggestions that you and

01:52:53.180 --> 01:52:57.980
[Amit Varma]: Ruben made. And I also want to explore one aspect of this bit where you said, quote,

01:52:57.980 --> 01:53:01.740
[Amit Varma]: countries such as India with large out of pocket expenditures in private health care

01:53:01.740 --> 01:53:06.980
[Amit Varma]: must restore the balance between health care and robust public health that focuses on improving

01:53:06.980 --> 01:53:12.820
[Amit Varma]: health outcomes for all only a capable state can deliver the latter. And what I'd like

01:53:12.820 --> 01:53:16.540
[Amit Varma]: to ask you about and elaborate on because I think this is a subject that confuses a

01:53:16.540 --> 01:53:21.500
[Amit Varma]: lot of people is the difference between health care and public health, that sometimes when

01:53:21.500 --> 01:53:27.060
[Amit Varma]: you talk about, you know, public health, people assume that, oh, this means that the state

01:53:27.060 --> 01:53:32.660
[Amit Varma]: will pay everybody's medical expenses, which is their health care expenses, which is, you

01:53:32.660 --> 01:53:36.540
[Amit Varma]: know, not the case, it means something entirely different, it means not necessarily treating

01:53:36.540 --> 01:53:40.980
[Amit Varma]: diseases, but preventing them from arising in the first place. So can you talk a little

01:53:40.980 --> 01:53:48.460
[Amit Varma]: bit about firstly, this distinction? And secondly, what can the state now do to sort of make

01:53:48.460 --> 01:53:54.540
[Amit Varma]: sure that whenever such a pandemic next occurs, its effects are relatively mitigated?

01:53:54.540 --> 01:53:59.380
[Guest]: So you're right. So we're talking about, you know, prevention of communicable diseases,

01:53:59.380 --> 01:54:04.500
[Guest]: prevention of infectious diseases, and everything that that can be done to prevent that, including

01:54:04.500 --> 01:54:11.860
[Guest]: say fumigating your streets to like making sure there's no saturated water that can be

01:54:11.860 --> 01:54:18.540
[Guest]: polluted, breeding sites for mosquitoes to ensuring that clean water available for citizens

01:54:18.540 --> 01:54:24.820
[Guest]: to drink, and you know, there's no chances of contamination, and also ensuring that your

01:54:24.820 --> 01:54:30.580
[Guest]: sanitation systems are not, you know, leaking into your water pipe systems. All of these

01:54:30.580 --> 01:54:37.580
[Guest]: things are unhealthy. I mean, the reason why they should exist is to have a healthier population

01:54:37.580 --> 01:54:44.180
[Guest]: and a healthier citizenry. So that, you know, a healthy population can, you know, be more

01:54:44.180 --> 01:54:50.820
[Guest]: productive and the gains are in terms of, again, increased revenues for the state. So

01:54:50.820 --> 01:54:58.100
[Guest]: that's the entire justification for having a public health system, not as opposed to

01:54:58.100 --> 01:55:03.500
[Guest]: a public health care system, which is taking care of like an individual sort of once there's

01:55:03.500 --> 01:55:10.140
[Guest]: a prognosis diagnosis, then helping with the curing and the you know, those other post

01:55:10.140 --> 01:55:16.740
[Guest]: illness treatments and so on. That's the major sort of difference. So what we are saying

01:55:16.740 --> 01:55:23.660
[Guest]: is that we need to have what do our departments of public health actually have power over

01:55:23.660 --> 01:55:29.100
[Guest]: say in a municipal body? Is it just looking after public hospitals? Or is it actually

01:55:29.100 --> 01:55:36.660
[Guest]: having a say in terms of, you know, what is your plan for augmenting your water infrastructure?

01:55:36.660 --> 01:55:41.060
[Guest]: What is your plan for augmenting your sewerage networks? And this is a point again that I'd

01:55:41.060 --> 01:55:47.100
[Guest]: made earlier that it's not this lack of thing. It is generally okay, as fumigation and so

01:55:47.100 --> 01:55:52.740
[Guest]: on these other activities may come under public health, but not this idea of infrastructure

01:55:52.740 --> 01:56:00.900
[Guest]: investment. And so you need to think about all of these state functions and state services

01:56:00.900 --> 01:56:07.140
[Guest]: from as a public health function, and not just a public service function. The second

01:56:07.140 --> 01:56:12.860
[Guest]: thing is, I mean, and we obviously caveat it by saying only a capable state can do this,

01:56:12.860 --> 01:56:22.540
[Guest]: which should clue you into our inherent cynicism to actually expecting a state that is not

01:56:22.540 --> 01:56:31.220
[Guest]: capable, which could be, many of our local governments are not up to the task to be able

01:56:31.220 --> 01:56:36.860
[Guest]: to do these things, and for aforementioned reasons of not having any real powers or revenues

01:56:36.860 --> 01:56:43.940
[Guest]: to be able to do that. So, A, all the public health needs to be looked at from this angle.

01:56:43.940 --> 01:56:50.660
[Guest]: It's very, even after a pandemic, I don't think that until we solve the problem of decentralization,

01:56:50.660 --> 01:56:58.420
[Guest]: we can't really expect at the municipal level, things to really change and governance systems

01:56:58.420 --> 01:57:03.700
[Guest]: to really change at the municipal level to actually look at it as a integrated thing.

01:57:03.700 --> 01:57:12.700
[Guest]: I mean, it would be great if maybe one or two cities tried it. I guess it may be easier

01:57:12.700 --> 01:57:22.820
[Guest]: to do and not in a like Bombay or Mumbai megacity, but in a smaller city in a relatively prosperous

01:57:22.820 --> 01:57:28.860
[Guest]: state government, maybe that may work. I mean, relatively prosperous state, a smaller city

01:57:28.860 --> 01:57:35.940
[Guest]: may be able to do it. But yeah, I think it's necessary, but it's not. I personally don't

01:57:35.940 --> 01:57:43.620
[Amit Varma]: see it happening, like anytime soon. Fair enough. Let's kind of move past this narrow

01:57:43.620 --> 01:57:48.740
[Amit Varma]: depressing context of what the state can do and all of that and just talk broadly about

01:57:48.740 --> 01:57:53.620
[Amit Varma]: cities and COVID in general. Now, what we've seen as we were discussing, you know, trends

01:57:53.620 --> 01:57:57.500
[Amit Varma]: of the past, you know, Ed Lazer wrote a great piece on this, which he forwarded to me, which

01:57:57.500 --> 01:58:01.660
[Amit Varma]: we'll link from the show notes, that pandemics happen, cities bounce back, that there's an

01:58:01.660 --> 01:58:07.140
[Amit Varma]: inherent need for cities and that kind of agglomeration. So, you know, things will continue

01:58:07.140 --> 01:58:12.180
[Amit Varma]: as usual. But at the same time, leave the pandemic aside, you know, is there a case

01:58:12.180 --> 01:58:16.620
[Amit Varma]: to be made that we need to redefine how we think of cities and how we think of networks

01:58:16.620 --> 01:58:22.420
[Amit Varma]: and communities, in the sense that I was reading this excellent paper for Bain & Co by Karen

01:58:22.420 --> 01:58:27.620
[Amit Varma]: Harris and a couple of co-authors where I came across this phrase, the cost of distance.

01:58:27.620 --> 01:58:32.380
[Amit Varma]: And her point, of course, is that the reason cities come together is because of the cost

01:58:32.380 --> 01:58:38.180
[Amit Varma]: of distance, because distance is expensive. It is hard to communicate and to send goods

01:58:38.180 --> 01:58:44.020
[Amit Varma]: and services across too much space. So therefore, you need to all conglomerate together in close

01:58:44.020 --> 01:58:48.100
[Amit Varma]: distances and that's why cities are there. But the trend that has been happening over

01:58:48.100 --> 01:58:53.740
[Amit Varma]: the last couple of decades is that the cost of distance is reducing massively. For example,

01:58:53.740 --> 01:58:58.420
[Amit Varma]: think about messages, or you can send an email to anyone anywhere in the world and it, you

01:58:58.420 --> 01:59:02.220
[Amit Varma]: know, you're not actually sending a letter where the cost of transporting a physical

01:59:02.220 --> 01:59:07.140
[Amit Varma]: letter, you know, gets the rises with the distance covered, you are reaching a stage

01:59:07.140 --> 01:59:12.260
[Amit Varma]: where you will have, say, delivery drones, where you will have eventually self driven

01:59:12.260 --> 01:59:17.540
[Amit Varma]: cars and trucks and all of that. So the cost of distance is reducing massively. And what

01:59:17.540 --> 01:59:23.940
[Amit Varma]: these lockdowns, you know, imposed because of COVID-19 have also taught us, it's a cliche

01:59:23.940 --> 01:59:29.620
[Amit Varma]: to say that we'll be working from home forever, I sincerely hope not. But what they've also

01:59:29.620 --> 01:59:35.620
[Amit Varma]: shown is that it is possible for a lot of people to work from a distance, that what

01:59:35.620 --> 01:59:41.060
[Amit Varma]: we really miss is not so much in terms of efficiency, but what at least, you know, I

01:59:41.060 --> 01:59:44.260
[Amit Varma]: of course, don't work for a company. So I, you know, I don't have personal experience

01:59:44.260 --> 01:59:48.140
[Amit Varma]: with that aspect of it, what I miss is just going out and physically meeting friends.

01:59:48.140 --> 01:59:52.820
[Amit Varma]: And that can, you know, change any way with time. But it seems to me that in many different

01:59:52.820 --> 01:59:59.060
[Amit Varma]: ways, therefore, as we redefine our communities, and we redefine who our neighbors are, because

01:59:59.060 --> 02:00:05.300
[Amit Varma]: I think the whole concept of who your neighbor is, is not necessarily only a geographical

02:00:05.300 --> 02:00:09.740
[Amit Varma]: concept that, you know, when we'd spoken about doing this episode three months ago, we'd

02:00:09.740 --> 02:00:13.100
[Amit Varma]: said that, you know, let the lockdown end and we are in Mumbai, we'll meet up at a studio

02:00:13.100 --> 02:00:17.780
[Amit Varma]: and do it. But now we've decided to play it safe. And we are doing it remotely, like I

02:00:17.780 --> 02:00:22.140
[Amit Varma]: record with my guests from all over the world. So that space doesn't matter, the distance

02:00:22.140 --> 02:00:26.420
[Amit Varma]: doesn't matter, it no longer matters so much that we are in the same city. In fact, you

02:00:26.420 --> 02:00:29.780
[Amit Varma]: know, up to a couple of years ago, I thought I can live in any city, it doesn't really

02:00:29.780 --> 02:00:33.980
[Amit Varma]: matter to me. And then I realized when the podcast took off that I have to be in Mumbai,

02:00:33.980 --> 02:00:38.020
[Amit Varma]: because I have access to a studio and I have access to some guests. So I have to be in

02:00:38.020 --> 02:00:41.660
[Amit Varma]: a big city. And now with this pandemic, I'm realizing that, hey, even that's actually

02:00:41.660 --> 02:00:45.780
[Amit Varma]: not really true. All I need is a great internet connection. And I'm sorted. You know, everything

02:00:45.780 --> 02:00:51.140
[Amit Varma]: else is remote. So there are these, sorry, if I feel like I'm rambling, but there are

02:00:51.140 --> 02:00:55.900
[Amit Varma]: these sort of two questions. One, that do you think that at a conceptual level, the

02:00:55.900 --> 02:01:03.380
[Amit Varma]: notion of a city and the notion of why it's necessary was going to change anyway, as time

02:01:03.380 --> 02:01:09.340
[Amit Varma]: progressed? And if so, do you feel that might have been accelerated by it coming into such

02:01:09.340 --> 02:01:13.740
[Amit Varma]: sharp and concrete focus because of the pandemic?

02:01:13.740 --> 02:01:23.300
[Guest]: To a certain extent, this is a lot more relevant to a developed country context. And to, you

02:01:23.300 --> 02:01:31.100
[Guest]: know, even in India, certain section of the population, right, who can sit at home and

02:01:31.100 --> 02:01:36.460
[Guest]: have a stable enough internet connection, although I can't claim that mine is stable

02:01:36.460 --> 02:01:43.300
[Guest]: at all. But there's even, okay, so taking care of like, let's say those constraints

02:01:43.300 --> 02:01:49.460
[Guest]: are taken care of, right? Everyone gets that great access to great internet. And, you know,

02:01:49.460 --> 02:01:54.740
[Guest]: so there's no problems of neat, you know, information technology, or all these things

02:01:54.740 --> 02:02:01.660
[Guest]: are taken care of. Why would you still want to be in a city? I think it is, in a sense,

02:02:01.660 --> 02:02:08.340
[Guest]: there is an idea of wanting to be able to do some things that cities can afford you

02:02:08.340 --> 02:02:14.580
[Guest]: to do that other things can't, you can't. So for instance, going to the, again, not

02:02:14.580 --> 02:02:20.720
[Guest]: not very relevant in other cases, but in Mumbai, you can enjoy a nice, like classical concert,

02:02:20.720 --> 02:02:26.300
[Guest]: you know, and the at the NCP and then the next day, you know, go to another film, sort

02:02:26.300 --> 02:02:33.500
[Guest]: of club and watch a lovely film and do all these other things which are possible, because

02:02:33.500 --> 02:02:39.620
[Guest]: these do arts and your culture needs some densities to be able to survive. And that's

02:02:39.620 --> 02:02:45.140
[Guest]: what cities afford. So it's not it, of course, it's your livelihoods that matter. And I bring

02:02:45.140 --> 02:02:50.260
[Guest]: you here in the first place. But what matters to you is also sort of something like going

02:02:50.260 --> 02:02:57.060
[Guest]: and watching a great movie at a film festival and going and watching a nice, you know, opera

02:02:57.060 --> 02:03:02.580
[Guest]: somewhere. And those things are not something that I don't think the cost of distance argument

02:03:02.580 --> 02:03:07.700
[Guest]: applies. And I still I think there are enough people that want to be able to sort of have

02:03:07.700 --> 02:03:14.420
[Guest]: Thai food one day and then have like, order in some Chinese the next day and, you know,

02:03:14.420 --> 02:03:19.340
[Guest]: enjoy some good food again. And, and these, these kinds of places will only thrive with

02:03:19.340 --> 02:03:27.380
[Guest]: this certain number of clientele there. So, in a sense, there is value to the city for

02:03:27.380 --> 02:03:34.060
[Guest]: all these other pleasures that it affords, for which will not be addressed by this thing

02:03:34.060 --> 02:03:40.460
[Guest]: of cost of distance going away. So you, you know, you can, of course, watch some concert

02:03:40.460 --> 02:03:47.020
[Guest]: online and rent a movie online. But I, I mean, I don't, I think I'll be, it'll be safe to

02:03:47.020 --> 02:03:53.540
[Guest]: say that it's not the same thing as watching a live performance. The other reason why cities

02:03:53.540 --> 02:03:59.380
[Guest]: are important is also the anonymity and the social mobility that they afford certain sections

02:03:59.380 --> 02:04:06.180
[Guest]: of people. If you are stuck in a rural farm somewhere with this, you know, same kind of

02:04:06.180 --> 02:04:12.220
[Guest]: oppressive systems around you, and you happen to be somebody who's not from, you know, one

02:04:12.220 --> 02:04:17.380
[Guest]: of the socially privileged communities over there, then, then moving to cities will afford

02:04:17.380 --> 02:04:23.660
[Guest]: you a level of anonymity, they'll afford you an opportunity for social mobility, which

02:04:23.660 --> 02:04:30.900
[Guest]: again, it's not something that, it's not a cost of distance problem per se. So I still

02:04:30.900 --> 02:04:37.940
[Guest]: think that as much as we think that cities are, you know, likely going to be redundant

02:04:37.940 --> 02:04:46.460
[Guest]: or you don't need cities around anymore, we undervalue the, these softer aspects of like

02:04:46.460 --> 02:04:55.540
[Guest]: the non-measurable aspect of urban living. And those I feel are not non-trivial. And

02:04:55.540 --> 02:05:00.980
[Guest]: they do sort of, you know, they will continue to persist. And that's why, I mean, I'm, I'm

02:05:00.980 --> 02:05:06.860
[Guest]: pretty optimistic that we, that cities are not going to go away. I mean, a lot of people

02:05:06.860 --> 02:05:11.980
[Guest]: may wish them away, but I don't think that that's going to happen.

02:05:11.980 --> 02:05:16.420
[Amit Varma]: No, I agree entirely with you. In fact, you know, I'm, I love cities, you know, whenever

02:05:16.420 --> 02:05:21.260
[Amit Varma]: I go on vacations or whatever, I'd rather go to a big city than to some really secluded

02:05:21.260 --> 02:05:25.340
[Amit Varma]: nice place on a hill or whatever, because just taking in that new life of a new city

02:05:25.340 --> 02:05:29.740
[Amit Varma]: is something I find wonderful. And both your reasons are great. And you know, the second

02:05:29.740 --> 02:05:33.620
[Amit Varma]: one that you gave me the social mobility reason, I thought that there, what applies that, you

02:05:33.620 --> 02:05:37.940
[Amit Varma]: know, if you're a Dalit stuck in a village with an entrenched and oppressive car system,

02:05:37.940 --> 02:05:42.020
[Amit Varma]: then forget the cost of distance, there is a cost to proximity. And you actually want

02:05:42.020 --> 02:05:47.280
[Amit Varma]: to put some distance between you and wherever you are. So, you know, that's a great reason.

02:05:47.280 --> 02:05:52.440
[Amit Varma]: And your other reason is something that I kind of viscerally feel like my being in Bombay,

02:05:52.440 --> 02:05:56.340
[Amit Varma]: the highlight of every year for me, clearly not yours, because I've never seen you there

02:05:56.340 --> 02:06:00.580
[Amit Varma]: is a mummy film festival, where I will just make sure that I have that week off and I

02:06:00.580 --> 02:06:05.020
[Amit Varma]: watch some 20 green films in those seven days. And it's just totally the highlight for me.

02:06:05.020 --> 02:06:08.740
[Amit Varma]: And that's made possible by the fact that there is a city. So there are all these viewers

02:06:08.740 --> 02:06:12.500
[Amit Varma]: and all the economies of scale work out. Now, one could argue that, hey, you could just

02:06:12.500 --> 02:06:18.060
[Amit Varma]: sit at home and on your big high definitions, screens, recreate the experience. But I guess

02:06:18.060 --> 02:06:22.100
[Amit Varma]: that depends on how much you value the social part of the experience. But one thing that

02:06:22.100 --> 02:06:26.340
[Amit Varma]: you definitely cannot recreate and that you will not have without cities is, you know,

02:06:26.340 --> 02:06:31.380
[Amit Varma]: speciality cuisine restaurants, because, you know, those depend on these large networks

02:06:31.380 --> 02:06:36.900
[Amit Varma]: of people to for those, you know, for it to make feasible to serve those little long tails.

02:06:36.900 --> 02:06:42.340
[Amit Varma]: So I couldn't agree more with all of this, as I think you've taken enough of your time

02:06:42.340 --> 02:06:46.500
[Amit Varma]: and you've been very patient and generous with your insights. I'll leave with a sort

02:06:46.500 --> 02:06:52.700
[Amit Varma]: of a question that you must have been expecting, which is that, you know, talking about not

02:06:52.700 --> 02:06:57.140
[Amit Varma]: just cities, but your work with cities and the way Indian cities are going and so on

02:06:57.140 --> 02:07:01.820
[Amit Varma]: and so forth, just in that context, over the next 10 years, what gives you hope and what

02:07:01.820 --> 02:07:03.300
[Amit Varma]: gives you despair?

02:07:03.300 --> 02:07:08.860
[Guest]: What gives me hope is actually this very famous. I don't know if it is actually that famous.

02:07:08.860 --> 02:07:13.580
[Guest]: Ellen Barry wrote a piece in New York Times about these girls who had come from Odisha

02:07:13.580 --> 02:07:19.620
[Guest]: to work in Bangalore in textile factory and just it was about their lives. And it was

02:07:19.620 --> 02:07:26.180
[Guest]: a lovely piece about how, where they went, what they did after work, and how for many

02:07:26.180 --> 02:07:31.220
[Guest]: of them, they were tasting freedom for the first time, financial freedom, freedom to

02:07:31.220 --> 02:07:39.020
[Guest]: discover and who they are. And that sort of, you know, that it's maybe I'm looking at it

02:07:39.020 --> 02:07:46.060
[Guest]: from a very raw instinctive perspective, but it gives me hope that that we are still affording

02:07:46.060 --> 02:07:53.900
[Guest]: these kinds of opportunities to people to actually be able to experience independence

02:07:53.900 --> 02:08:00.780
[Guest]: and freedom and thinking about what their dreams and aspirations are. And to come to

02:08:00.780 --> 02:08:06.740
[Guest]: what gives me despair, it is that, you know, that story was written a few years ago, and

02:08:06.740 --> 02:08:13.460
[Guest]: things have changed since then, right? And we're seeing, I mean, the economic situation

02:08:13.460 --> 02:08:20.980
[Guest]: is not great. And the pandemic has just completely led to all sorts of breakdowns of economic

02:08:20.980 --> 02:08:27.780
[Guest]: systems, social systems, even. And, I mean, as much as I'd like to believe, I'm not, I

02:08:27.780 --> 02:08:33.380
[Guest]: think it's going to be a long time coming before we actually get back to those levels

02:08:33.380 --> 02:08:41.340
[Guest]: of, you know, growth and prosperity. And that track, going back to that track of growth

02:08:41.340 --> 02:08:46.380
[Guest]: and prosperity is going to take us some time. And things can, I mean, things can go wrong

02:08:46.380 --> 02:08:50.540
[Guest]: in all kinds of ways. So it's not a given that we get there eventually. And, you know,

02:08:50.540 --> 02:08:56.900
[Guest]: it's just a small few years of, but it's those few years are very, very, very costly. And

02:08:56.900 --> 02:09:02.580
[Guest]: in terms of what they mean for so many millions of people who are experiencing, you know,

02:09:02.580 --> 02:09:08.740
[Guest]: going back under the poverty line, and so on. So that gives me some, some despair.

02:09:08.740 --> 02:09:13.740
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's a lot of despair and some that I share with you. So I shall end on the note

02:09:13.740 --> 02:09:17.780
[Amit Varma]: of hope that, you know, this is not the last that I've seen of you on the scene and the

02:09:17.780 --> 02:09:21.140
[Amit Varma]: unseen and hopefully the next time we can record in person. Thank you so much for coming

